process.

246
00:14:32.122 --> 00:14:35.942
And those mutational signatures can be generated either by endogenous

247
00:14:36.002 --> 00:14:39.822
mutational processes. We all, as we live, we generate

248
00:14:39.902 --> 00:14:43.802
mutations, and also by the mutational

249
00:14:43.862 --> 00:14:47.642
processes that we're particularly interested in in this context, which is the

250
00:14:47.662 --> 00:14:49.202
exogenous exposures.

251
00:14:51.282 --> 00:14:55.172
All genomes carry mutations from multiple mutational signatures,

252
00:14:55.262 --> 00:14:57.382
so they have to be separated from each other.

253
00:14:58.042 --> 00:15:01.722
And at that time, in the middle of about 2015,

254
00:15:02.662 --> 00:15:06.202
the theoretical ways of doing that, the conceptual and

255
00:15:06.242 --> 00:15:09.802
operational, computational, and mathematical approaches were put in place,

256
00:15:10.362 --> 00:15:13.822
which allowed one to extract mutational signatures.

257
00:15:14.582 --> 00:15:17.602
And this is a mutational signature.

258
00:15:17.642 --> 00:15:20.402
The patterns were pretty familiar, but I'll just go through.

259
00:15:20.442 --> 00:15:24.012
You can see there the six types of base substitution,

260
00:15:24.442 --> 00:15:27.902
C to A, C to G, C to T, T to A, T to C, and T to G.

261
00:15:28.562 --> 00:15:32.522
But the classification of base substitutions that we use is elaborated

262
00:15:32.562 --> 00:15:36.462
from there. We include the base immediately before the mutated

263
00:15:36.502 --> 00:15:39.822
base and the base after the mutated base, and that leads to a

264
00:15:39.842 --> 00:15:43.582
classification of 96 different base substitutions,

265
00:15:44.682 --> 00:15:48.362
which are represented there as a 96 bar chart.

266
00:15:48.722 --> 00:15:52.562
And in this particular mutational signature, most of the mutations

267
00:15:52.602 --> 00:15:55.102
are blue, so they're C to A mutations.

268
00:15:55.802 --> 00:15:59.482
And that pattern has been associated with tobacco

269
00:15:59.582 --> 00:16:02.582
smoke chemicals, both in vivo and in vitro.

270
00:16:02.892 --> 00:16:06.882
And if you see that pattern in a tissue sample, you

271
00:16:06.942 --> 00:16:10.682
can be pretty sure that that person has been exposed to tobacco smoke.

272
00:16:13.142 --> 00:16:16.942
Subsequently, the sequencing of tens of thousands of cancer

273
00:16:17.022 --> 00:16:20.922
genomes and normal genomes has

274
00:16:21.042 --> 00:16:22.202
led to the discovery of

275
00:16:23.022 --> 00:16:26.782
many mutational signatures, and there's now a repertoire of about

276
00:16:26.822 --> 00:16:30.782
80 different mutational signatures that are found naturally

277
00:16:30.842 --> 00:16:33.502
in human tissues, whether they're cancer or

278
00:16:34.362 --> 00:16:35.182
normal tissues.

279
00:16:37.502 --> 00:16:40.792
So in order to use the now available

280
00:16:40.902 --> 00:16:44.422
technology and conceptual framework, Mutagraphs was

281
00:16:44.522 --> 00:16:46.702
structured into six work packages.

282
00:16:47.582 --> 00:16:51.391
First, mutational epidemiology, looking for mutational

283
00:16:51.422 --> 00:16:55.282
signatures in five cancer types in very large numbers of cases

284
00:16:55.322 --> 00:16:58.662
across five continents. Then to develop

285
00:16:58.702 --> 00:17:02.472
computational methods for mutational signature analysis to look for

286
00:17:02.502 --> 00:17:06.062
mutational signatures in rodents exposed to carcinogens,

287
00:17:06.702 --> 00:17:10.623
to look for the signatures in cells exposed to mutagens, to

288
00:17:10.662 --> 00:17:14.583
look more broadly at mutational burdens and signatures

289
00:17:14.623 --> 00:17:18.322
in normal cells, and then to specifically focus on one

290
00:17:18.383 --> 00:17:21.762
type of normal cell, normal white blood cells, to see if

291
00:17:22.682 --> 00:17:26.522
presence detectability of mutational signatures there could be used more

292
00:17:26.562 --> 00:17:28.282
widely in epidemiology.

293
00:17:30.782 --> 00:17:31.782
And so from the

294
00:17:32.742 --> 00:17:36.682
numbers, the multiple observations that were made during the course

295
00:17:36.742 --> 00:17:40.342
of those eight years in Mutagraphs, I've picked out really three

296
00:17:40.402 --> 00:17:44.082
headline discoveries that are thematic

297
00:17:44.182 --> 00:17:47.822
and give a sense of what can be learnt about the causes of

298
00:17:47.862 --> 00:17:51.422
cancer and which continuing work will hopefully

299
00:17:51.462 --> 00:17:54.162
generate more data and more results in the future.

300
00:17:55.422 --> 00:17:59.322
So from that mutational epidemiology part of it, a collection

301
00:17:59.382 --> 00:18:01.602
was made around the world of

302
00:18:03.062 --> 00:18:04.282
eight types of cancer,

303
00:18:05.762 --> 00:18:09.732
which were from 5,000 participants, from which we got cancer and

304
00:18:09.782 --> 00:18:12.222
normal samples and epidemiological metadata.

305
00:18:13.032 --> 00:18:16.982
They came from 30 countries, and all these cancers were whole

306
00:18:17.022 --> 00:18:20.562
genome sequenced. In the map you see in front of you, the blue

307
00:18:20.622 --> 00:18:24.242
represents the parts of the world which were included in this

308
00:18:24.322 --> 00:18:24.702
study.

309
00:18:26.682 --> 00:18:30.521
So the first of the headlines came from studying

310
00:18:30.582 --> 00:18:34.260
esophageal squamous carcinomaAnd now in this map of the

311
00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:38.270
world, the dark blue indicates those parts which have a high

312
00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:42.230
incidence of esophageal squamous carcinoma, and the parts which are

313
00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:43.890
in light blue have a low incidence.

314
00:18:44.140 --> 00:18:47.950
And this is a rather unusual distribution for any cancer type.

315
00:18:48.390 --> 00:18:52.310
You can see there is a high incidence down the east coast

316
00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:55.670
of Africa and across that belt of Central Asia.

317
00:18:56.610 --> 00:19:00.070
That's very unusual. And the differences in cancer

318
00:19:00.150 --> 00:19:03.530
incidence rates between the dark blue and the light blue are huge.

319
00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:05.790
Those are 10 to 20-fold differences.

320
00:19:06.090 --> 00:19:10.070
Exactly what you would expect if there is some

321
00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:13.770
major exposure taking place, which is causing those

322
00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:17.610
differences. You can never exclude that there might be some form of

323
00:19:17.650 --> 00:19:21.630
genetic inherited population difference, but differences

324
00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:25.570
of this size are very unlikely to be due

325
00:19:25.650 --> 00:19:26.130
to those.

326
00:19:26.990 --> 00:19:30.850
So this was our starting point, to look at cancers from those

327
00:19:30.890 --> 00:19:34.880
regions to see what we could find. And there were samples

328
00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:38.790
collected from eight countries, over 500 of them, and

329
00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:41.890
these were whole genome sequenced.

330
00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:47.650
So what did we find? We first of all found we could analyze the data for

331
00:19:47.770 --> 00:19:51.470
sure, and we could find the signatures of a well-known endogenous

332
00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:55.490
mutational process, the APOBEC mutational signatures, which are

333
00:19:55.550 --> 00:19:59.010
due to the APOBEC enzyme family, which are cytosine

334
00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:02.910
deaminases. You find these in many cancer types and also in

335
00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:06.850
some normal tissues. The really unusual thing about esophageal

336
00:20:06.870 --> 00:20:10.420
squamous carcinoma is just how pervasive this

337
00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:14.010
was. Essentially every case had the

338
00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:16.810
APOBEC mutational signatures in it.

339
00:20:16.890 --> 00:20:20.810
Quite unusual, and something that still should continue to be

340
00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:24.750
borne in mind as we think through the implications of the results I'll

341
00:20:24.810 --> 00:20:25.790
tell you about now.

342
00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:29.810
We also could detect

343
00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:33.530
signatures of tobacco and alcohol exposure.

344
00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:37.430
And that's important because it means the system was working in the way that we

345
00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:41.030
wanted it to. We could look at the mutations, we could

346
00:20:41.209 --> 00:20:44.090
extract the signatures, and we could see the patterns of

347
00:20:44.870 --> 00:20:47.710
alcohol exposure and tobacco exposure.

348
00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:51.230
And because we had epidemiological data, we could see that they

349
00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:54.990
correlated with individuals who were smokers and who were drinkers.

350
00:20:56.510 --> 00:21:00.010
However, then when we looked at the data set as a whole,

351
00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:04.170
there were no major differences across these eight countries in

352
00:21:04.190 --> 00:21:07.869
mutation burdens or mutational signatures between them.

353
00:21:09.030 --> 00:21:11.990
There was no new mutational signature there,

354
00:21:12.810 --> 00:21:16.750
nothing that we could look at and say, "Well, yes, that's

355
00:21:16.790 --> 00:21:20.610
likely to be accounting for these huge differences," this huge

356
00:21:20.690 --> 00:21:23.150
exposure which we assumed to be there.

357
00:21:23.550 --> 00:21:27.130
It was a truly resounding negative.

358
00:21:29.250 --> 00:21:30.510
Now, around this time,

359
00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:36.030
the results were beginning to emerge from the rodent studies.

360
00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:40.490
And in those rodent studies, mice had been exposed to about 20

361
00:21:40.650 --> 00:21:44.570
putative environmental human carcinogens, and these

362
00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:48.570
were known or probable or possible carcinogens as defined by

363
00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:50.930
the International Agency for Research on Cancer.

364
00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:55.490
And all of them caused significantly increased tumor incidence in these

365
00:21:55.530 --> 00:21:58.810
mice. So they were all acting as carcinogens.

366
00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:06.030
However, when the tumors from these mice were sequenced,

367
00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:10.520
only three of those carcinogens produced

368
00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:13.410
what you might have expected from a mutagen.

369
00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:16.050
In other words, tumors with a lot of mutations

370
00:22:17.290 --> 00:22:21.190
and tumors with a lot of mutations with distinctive

371
00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:24.430
mutational signatures. That's what you'd have expected

372
00:22:24.550 --> 00:22:28.070
if the tumors had been caused by a mutagen.

373
00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:32.870
But only three of the carcinogens showed

374
00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:35.190
that pattern, the three that are highlighted there.

375
00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:38.490
The remaining 17 did not.

376
00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:43.680
And so that led to the consideration that

377
00:22:43.730 --> 00:22:47.590
perhaps not all carcinogens are mutagens.

378
00:22:48.370 --> 00:22:51.930
So mutagens change mutation loads and they change mutational

379
00:22:51.969 --> 00:22:54.890
signatures. There's that signature there.

380
00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:58.890
But there had been decades of work on a different sort of

381
00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:01.650
carcinogen, which were then called promoters.

382
00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:05.950
And promoters allowed preexisting

383
00:23:05.990 --> 00:23:09.730
mutations to emerge as causing cancer,

384
00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:12.550
but they were not in themselves mutagens.

385
00:23:13.450 --> 00:23:17.420
So promoters change the landscape of normal cell clones with

386
00:23:17.450 --> 00:23:21.170
driver mutations. They change the selective environment.

387
00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:26.510
And that has been given a sort of material reality over the last year

388
00:23:26.570 --> 00:23:30.530
or two because the structure

389
00:23:30.670 --> 00:23:34.250
of mutated clones in normal tissues has become evident.

390
00:23:34.710 --> 00:23:38.690
And that square on the right there is representing

391
00:23:38.750 --> 00:23:42.470
about a centimeter squared of normal esophagus, and each of

392
00:23:42.530 --> 00:23:46.270
those circles there represents a clone of cells.

393
00:23:46.310 --> 00:23:49.910
And if it's colored in, that clone of cells has got a

394
00:23:49.950 --> 00:23:53.490
driver mutation in a cancer gene, a driver

395
00:23:53.550 --> 00:23:56.910
mutation which you would be perfectly happy to find in a cancer

396
00:23:57.510 --> 00:24:01.110
and assume that that mutated gene was implicated in

397
00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:02.790
causing the cancer. But this

398
00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:06.270
is what a normal esophagus looks like.

399
00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:10.710
So it's normal because it looks normal down the microscope, and it's

400
00:24:10.790 --> 00:24:13.830
normal because we all have this going on in us.

401
00:24:13.870 --> 00:24:16.810
And when we get to about the age of 70 or 80,

402
00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:21.430
most of our esophagus is covered by these mutated clones with driver

403
00:24:21.470 --> 00:24:25.370
mutations. So you can see how these promoters might

404
00:24:25.470 --> 00:24:29.230
work, because they could increase the number of those

405
00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:33.230
clones, they could increase the size of the clones, they could change

406
00:24:33.290 --> 00:24:37.110
the mutated genes that are present in those clones, and all of that

407
00:24:37.590 --> 00:24:41.350
could result in a higher risk of the tissue

408
00:24:41.410 --> 00:24:45.270
spawning a cancer. So that's how promoters are thought to

409
00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:49.306
work.Today, some are calling these selectogens,

410
00:24:49.646 --> 00:24:53.076
putting the whole thing within a conceptual framework of somatic

411
00:24:53.246 --> 00:24:56.826
evolution, for which you need mutations, for which mutagens

412
00:24:56.906 --> 00:25:00.426
contribute, and then a changed selective environment

413
00:25:00.806 --> 00:25:04.546
and agents that change that selective environment and encourage

414
00:25:04.566 --> 00:25:08.026
the growth of those clones, some are calling selectogens.

415
00:25:08.986 --> 00:25:09.206
So

416
00:25:10.546 --> 00:25:14.266
probably many of those human carcinogens that were

417
00:25:14.346 --> 00:25:15.026
used in the

418
00:25:15.946 --> 00:25:17.366
mouse studies were

419
00:25:18.346 --> 00:25:21.246
selectogens or promoters, and potentially

420
00:25:22.026 --> 00:25:24.546
whatever is causing that big increase in

421
00:25:25.466 --> 00:25:28.466
esophageal squamous carcinoma in East Africa and in Asia,

422
00:25:29.026 --> 00:25:31.866
possibly that is also a promoter.

423
00:25:33.746 --> 00:25:35.026
So the next cancer type

424
00:25:36.246 --> 00:25:39.926
was renal clear cell cancer, and here the headline is very

425
00:25:39.946 --> 00:25:40.895
different indeed.

426
00:25:42.446 --> 00:25:46.026
You can see that the distribution of renal cancer incidence across the world is

427
00:25:46.086 --> 00:25:50.026
very different from I showed you for esophageal squamous carcinoma, in some

428
00:25:50.046 --> 00:25:53.826
ways, much more familiar. The dark blue areas are in high-income

429
00:25:53.926 --> 00:25:57.726
countries and where cancer is generally higher, and the

430
00:25:57.826 --> 00:25:58.926
light blue areas

431
00:26:00.226 --> 00:26:01.546
in low-income countries.

432
00:26:02.646 --> 00:26:06.506
For renal clear cell cancer, about 1,000 cases were collected

433
00:26:06.886 --> 00:26:10.686
from 11 countries and were sequenced.

434
00:26:11.846 --> 00:26:15.626
So in renal cancer, we could find evidence of

435
00:26:15.866 --> 00:26:18.866
exposures due to exogenous mutagens.

436
00:26:19.226 --> 00:26:22.826
And we'll start with this one. These two signatures,

437
00:26:22.906 --> 00:26:26.346
SBS22A and 22B, you can see they're

438
00:26:26.486 --> 00:26:30.266
composed mainly of these gray mutations, which are T to A mutations.

439
00:26:31.326 --> 00:26:35.286
Very distinctively, we found them clustered

440
00:26:35.346 --> 00:26:39.276
in one geographical area in the southeast of Europe, in Romania,

441
00:26:39.356 --> 00:26:41.146
and Serbia, and Bulgaria.

442
00:26:42.586 --> 00:26:46.346
And there they were present in something like 70% of the cancers.

443
00:26:46.576 --> 00:26:50.566
So most of the cancers had them. Because of

444
00:26:50.626 --> 00:26:54.466
that, because these mutational signatures are so distinctive, we can know

445
00:26:54.506 --> 00:26:58.306
what the agent causing this is, and it is a

446
00:26:58.366 --> 00:27:01.686
set of plant products called aristolochic acids.

447
00:27:02.526 --> 00:27:06.186
The aristolochia genus is quite a widespread genus of

448
00:27:06.196 --> 00:27:06.576
plant,

449
00:27:07.486 --> 00:27:10.066
and many of the species within it produce

450
00:27:10.746 --> 00:27:14.086
mutagens that are shown there, which are known to be

451
00:27:14.126 --> 00:27:15.066
carcinogenic.

452
00:27:16.026 --> 00:27:19.386
So in Southeast Europe, there is

453
00:27:19.466 --> 00:27:23.086
a major exposure to aristolochic acids.

454
00:27:25.146 --> 00:27:27.806
The next observation was this one.

455
00:27:28.086 --> 00:27:31.926
So signature SBS12, which is composed of

456
00:27:31.986 --> 00:27:35.566
those green T to C mutations predominantly, we

457
00:27:35.646 --> 00:27:39.606
found only in Japan. None of the other countries that

458
00:27:39.666 --> 00:27:43.606
we looked at or indeed have looked at subsequently has

459
00:27:43.646 --> 00:27:44.726
this signature in it.

460
00:27:45.846 --> 00:27:49.126
So another very geographically localized

461
00:27:50.306 --> 00:27:53.846
signature, probably due to a geographically localized

462
00:27:53.926 --> 00:27:57.506
exposure, this time of completely unknown

463
00:27:57.586 --> 00:28:01.275
cause. We have no idea what the underlying

464
00:28:01.426 --> 00:28:02.126
agent is.

465
00:28:03.326 --> 00:28:04.286
And then the third one

466
00:28:05.206 --> 00:28:08.886
is this signature, SBS40B. This one is more

467
00:28:08.946 --> 00:28:12.186
ubiquitous, but it does have geographical variation

468
00:28:12.386 --> 00:28:16.026
in incidence, high prevalence in Czech

469
00:28:16.426 --> 00:28:18.386
Republic, low prevalence in Japan.

470
00:28:18.726 --> 00:28:22.686
The amount of this that one finds in a country correlates

471
00:28:22.726 --> 00:28:26.146
with that country's incidence of clear cell renal cancer.

472
00:28:27.386 --> 00:28:29.986
But it is also of unknown cause.

473
00:28:33.266 --> 00:28:36.546
So in renal clear cell cancer, we found multiple

474
00:28:36.706 --> 00:28:40.506
likely exogenous mutagen exposures, including known

475
00:28:40.566 --> 00:28:42.826
carcinogens, the aristolochic acids.

476
00:28:45.646 --> 00:28:49.486
And in Southeast Europe and in Japan, and

477
00:28:49.546 --> 00:28:53.366
certainly for signature 40B, if that is a mutagen, tens of millions of

478
00:28:53.406 --> 00:28:55.046
people are being exposed.

479
00:28:57.566 --> 00:29:00.346
And they're being exposed passively and silently.

480
00:29:00.396 --> 00:29:02.706
They don't know they're being exposed, and they're not

481
00:29:04.326 --> 00:29:08.286
doing anything to be exposed. It's unusual, and it's

482
00:29:08.326 --> 00:29:09.466
a silent exposure.

483
00:29:10.526 --> 00:29:14.406
You can see both known and unknown mutagens, the aristolochic

484
00:29:14.486 --> 00:29:17.206
acids, and then the others that we don't know the cause of.

485
00:29:17.946 --> 00:29:21.386
We also don't know what the consequences are, to be honest.

486
00:29:21.926 --> 00:29:22.366
We know that

487
00:29:23.266 --> 00:29:26.926
some of these are very likely to be exposures, but the consequences, the

488
00:29:26.966 --> 00:29:30.866
cancer risk they confer, that we do not know at the moment.

489
00:29:32.586 --> 00:29:35.826
So the final headline is in colorectal cancer,

490
00:29:36.706 --> 00:29:40.626
where the incidence map is, again, that familiar one,

491
00:29:40.666 --> 00:29:44.256
not so different from renal clear cell cancer, with a high incidence in

492
00:29:44.706 --> 00:29:48.566
high-income countries and low incidence in low-income countries.

493
00:29:49.306 --> 00:29:52.866
Here we sequenced about 1,000 cancers from 11

494
00:29:52.966 --> 00:29:53.566
countries.

495
00:29:54.946 --> 00:29:58.866
And the interest in colorectal cancer has

496
00:29:58.926 --> 00:30:02.846
another dimension to that. In addition to the geographical

497
00:30:02.946 --> 00:30:05.306
variation, there has been temporal variation.

498
00:30:05.586 --> 00:30:09.226
There's been temporal variation over the last 80 years, with some

499
00:30:09.286 --> 00:30:13.206
countries showing a rather extraordinary rise in

500
00:30:13.586 --> 00:30:17.426
colorectal cancer, countries like Japan and Korea, for example.

501
00:30:17.966 --> 00:30:21.726
But over the last 40 years, there has been a very distinctive

502
00:30:21.826 --> 00:30:24.806
rise in early-onset colorectal cancer,

503
00:30:25.506 --> 00:30:29.306
represented in this figure. It's present in many countries.

504
00:30:29.666 --> 00:30:32.966
It's present in many men and women.

505
00:30:33.066 --> 00:30:36.946
And the way to read this chart is that if one is

506
00:30:37.046 --> 00:30:37.126
a

507
00:30:38.086 --> 00:30:41.156
male born in England in 1990,

508
00:30:42.086 --> 00:30:44.226
then one has a fivefold

509
00:30:45.946 --> 00:30:49.866
higher chance of developing early-onset colorectal cancer than if

510
00:30:49.886 --> 00:30:52.866
one had been a male born in England in 1960.

511
00:30:53.146 --> 00:30:56.706
So it's a really steeply rising risk of colorectal

512
00:30:56.766 --> 00:31:01.154
cancer.So

513
00:31:01.194 --> 00:31:05.054
in sequencing those thousand cases of colorectal cancer from around the

514
00:31:05.094 --> 00:31:08.934
world, the major mutational signature of interest is

515
00:31:08.974 --> 00:31:09.394
this one,

516
00:31:10.254 --> 00:31:11.434
SBS88,

517
00:31:12.314 --> 00:31:16.254
which we know is caused by a

518
00:31:16.294 --> 00:31:18.214
mutagen called colibactin.

519
00:31:19.314 --> 00:31:19.614
And

520
00:31:20.614 --> 00:31:23.454
this is a mutagen that's produced by a strain of E.

521
00:31:23.534 --> 00:31:27.454
coli in the microbiome. It's got an extra 50 kb of genome, which

522
00:31:27.514 --> 00:31:29.614
allows it to make colibactin.

523
00:31:31.554 --> 00:31:35.254
SBS88 is found in normal colorectal epithelium.

524
00:31:35.414 --> 00:31:37.914
This is what you'd expect if it is an exposure.

525
00:31:37.994 --> 00:31:41.974
Exposures usually affect normal tissues before they

526
00:31:42.554 --> 00:31:43.534
spawn cancers.

527
00:31:45.374 --> 00:31:49.174
It's interesting because the mutations are imprinted early in life,

528
00:31:49.314 --> 00:31:52.914
and this chimes because those rises in early

529
00:31:52.954 --> 00:31:56.854
onset colorectal cancer, they suggest

530
00:31:56.894 --> 00:32:00.614
that there has been a new exposure during the middle part of the last century, and

531
00:32:00.694 --> 00:32:03.724
that exposure almost certainly is happening in children and

532
00:32:03.854 --> 00:32:07.714
adolescents to give colorectal cancer of that sort of age.

533
00:32:08.654 --> 00:32:10.484
So the fact that this

534
00:32:11.734 --> 00:32:15.674
mutagen is causing mutations very early in life, during the first five

535
00:32:15.714 --> 00:32:16.394
years of life,

536
00:32:17.354 --> 00:32:20.874
has a consistency with that. And it's common.

537
00:32:21.734 --> 00:32:25.294
In looking at the normal colon of about 100

538
00:32:25.354 --> 00:32:29.214
children recently, about 40% of them in the UK who

539
00:32:29.254 --> 00:32:32.534
were born within the last 20 years have got

540
00:32:32.554 --> 00:32:33.314
colibactin

541
00:32:34.174 --> 00:32:37.114
mutational signature in their normal colon.

542
00:32:37.474 --> 00:32:41.314
So it's a common mutagenic exposure.

543
00:32:42.854 --> 00:32:46.844
The interesting observation from the Mutagraphs project was

544
00:32:46.874 --> 00:32:49.194
then when we looked in the colorectal cancers,

545
00:32:50.474 --> 00:32:54.334
there was a difference between the prevalence of the colibactin

546
00:32:54.454 --> 00:32:58.254
signature in cancers of different

547
00:32:58.314 --> 00:33:01.814
ages of diagnosis. So if you look at the green bar on the right,

548
00:33:02.234 --> 00:33:06.124
those are cancers, colorectal cancers, diagnosed at 70 or more, and

549
00:33:06.174 --> 00:33:08.674
10% of them have got the colibactin signature in.

550
00:33:09.094 --> 00:33:12.974
Whereas if we look at cancers diagnosed under the

551
00:33:12.994 --> 00:33:16.234
age of 40 in the purple bar, it's more than a third of them.

552
00:33:16.574 --> 00:33:20.394
So the colibactin mutational signature is being enriched in early onset

553
00:33:20.514 --> 00:33:21.694
colorectal cancer.

554
00:33:25.054 --> 00:33:28.834
So in this tumor type, we find multiple

555
00:33:28.874 --> 00:33:32.134
exogenous mutagen exposures, SBS18 and

556
00:33:32.194 --> 00:33:36.134
colibactin, but actually a number of others too that I won't talk about.

557
00:33:37.554 --> 00:33:41.374
These are quite common. Colibactin and SBS8 is probably the most

558
00:33:41.434 --> 00:33:43.494
common, but the others are also common.

559
00:33:43.534 --> 00:33:47.014
They show substantial geographic variation.

560
00:33:47.074 --> 00:33:51.034
So in some parts of the world, the other mutational signatures, which

561
00:33:51.074 --> 00:33:54.754
are also quite likely to be due to mutagen exposures from the

562
00:33:54.794 --> 00:33:57.174
microbiome, are the most common.

563
00:33:59.254 --> 00:34:03.134
Most of them are unknown cause, but as I've just said, probably

564
00:34:03.174 --> 00:34:07.114
many of them are also derived from the microbiome as

565
00:34:07.394 --> 00:34:08.314
colibactin is.

566
00:34:09.495 --> 00:34:13.444
And for many of them, they follow that same pattern that the mutations

567
00:34:13.475 --> 00:34:15.094
are imprinted early in life.

568
00:34:17.614 --> 00:34:21.495
So SBS88 is enriched in early onset colorectal cancer,

569
00:34:21.894 --> 00:34:25.814
so that has spawned the hypothesis that over the last 100

570
00:34:25.874 --> 00:34:29.834
years, there has been an increase in prevalence of colibactin-producing

571
00:34:29.874 --> 00:34:31.554
microbes in many countries.

572
00:34:32.834 --> 00:34:34.314
And that that increase

573
00:34:35.114 --> 00:34:38.594
and the additional mutational burden it confers in the

574
00:34:39.114 --> 00:34:42.915
normal colons of children is causing the increase in early

575
00:34:42.984 --> 00:34:46.634
onset colorectal cancer that's been observed over the last 40 years.

576
00:34:47.344 --> 00:34:51.274
So this hypothesis is being now investigated, and

577
00:34:51.314 --> 00:34:55.174
you will hear more about it if you attend tomorrow's plenary, to which

578
00:34:55.214 --> 00:34:57.734
Ludmil Alexandrov will talk more about this work.

579
00:34:59.734 --> 00:35:02.074
So in summary, for the whole of Mutagraphs,

580
00:35:03.014 --> 00:35:05.284
some human carcinogens may

581
00:35:06.354 --> 00:35:10.174
be promoters or selectogens, and possibly it's better to talk about this

582
00:35:10.274 --> 00:35:14.094
that all carcinogens have some mutagenic

583
00:35:14.154 --> 00:35:18.064
activity, and all of them have some selectogenic activity, and it's the

584
00:35:18.134 --> 00:35:21.934
balance between those that causes how well they cause

585
00:35:21.994 --> 00:35:22.393
cancer.

586
00:35:23.744 --> 00:35:27.474
That there are population scale silent mutagen exposures

587
00:35:27.534 --> 00:35:31.144
which exist. We weren't aware of these previously, and the

588
00:35:31.234 --> 00:35:34.954
sequencing and the mutational signatures allows them to be identified.

589
00:35:35.774 --> 00:35:39.634
And that microbiome-derived mutagens may increase colorectal cancer

590
00:35:39.694 --> 00:35:43.534
risk and cause the current rise in early onset colorectal

591
00:35:43.594 --> 00:35:44.014
cancer.

592
00:35:45.204 --> 00:35:49.174
And that mutational epidemiology generally offers an alternative

593
00:35:49.254 --> 00:35:52.184
strategy for investigating the causes of cancer.

594
00:35:53.104 --> 00:35:56.394
There are literally hundreds of people, as you can imagine, with all those

595
00:35:56.434 --> 00:36:00.343
collections over in all those countries that need to be thanked for doing

596
00:36:00.394 --> 00:36:04.254
this work. Some of the people who worked on the genomics are

597
00:36:04.294 --> 00:36:08.084
shown here, and I'd like to thank Cancer Grand Challenges,

598
00:36:08.374 --> 00:36:12.154
first of all, for the conception of the Grand Challenge, second of all, for putting

599
00:36:12.164 --> 00:36:15.994
the challenge to work on mutational signatures, and third of all, for

600
00:36:16.054 --> 00:36:19.854
the really considerate and thoughtful way that they helped us manage

601
00:36:19.874 --> 00:36:22.894
Mutagraphs through its eight years of existence. Thank you very much.

602
00:36:29.834 --> 00:36:30.534
Thank you, Mike.

603
00:36:31.434 --> 00:36:33.634
Next we have Alan Balmain.

604
00:36:34.474 --> 00:36:37.574
Alan was originally a chemist, studied chemistry at the University of

605
00:36:37.634 --> 00:36:41.264
Glasgow and carried out his post-doctoral work in France and then

606
00:36:41.294 --> 00:36:41.694
Germany.

607
00:36:42.574 --> 00:36:46.014
He has been professor at UCSF for

608
00:36:46.814 --> 00:36:49.533
some time now. 15 years, maybe longer.

609
00:36:50.714 --> 00:36:54.654
And leads a group that uses systemic or systems genetics, I should say,

610
00:36:54.734 --> 00:36:57.064
approaches to understand cancer complexity.

611
00:36:58.094 --> 00:37:01.314
He's been a leading light in the field of selectogens or promoters.

612
00:37:01.954 --> 00:37:05.854
He's been working on the Benham Bloom model for much of his

613
00:37:05.874 --> 00:37:06.234
career.

614
00:37:07.134 --> 00:37:10.654
And his recent work is really beginning to describe very nicely at a molecular

615
00:37:10.754 --> 00:37:13.862
level-How those original observations by Bern Bloom in

616
00:37:13.902 --> 00:37:17.782
1947 pan out in the skin papilloma

617
00:37:17.862 --> 00:37:21.692
model in mice. He's co-team lead of the

618
00:37:21.782 --> 00:37:25.602
Cancer Grand Challenge team PROMINENT, which seeks to understand how

619
00:37:25.702 --> 00:37:29.502
latent mutated cells in normal tissues become activated by

620
00:37:29.522 --> 00:37:32.722
promoters, as you heard from Mike earlier, to cause cancer.

621
00:37:33.322 --> 00:37:36.082
He's also a Fellow of the Royal Society since 2015.

622
00:37:36.702 --> 00:37:40.552
In the US, he was elected fellow of the AACR Academy, fellow of the

623
00:37:40.562 --> 00:37:42.802
American Association for the Advancement of Science.

624
00:37:43.142 --> 00:37:46.242
He's received numerous awards, including the

625
00:37:46.422 --> 00:37:50.242
2024 Princess Takamatsu Foundation Award Lectureship.

626
00:37:50.932 --> 00:37:52.322
It's a great pleasure to introduce you, Alan.

627
00:37:52.462 --> 00:37:54.062
We're looking forward to hearing the latest update.

628
00:38:02.302 --> 00:38:05.002
Let me see if this... Ah, okay.

629
00:38:07.282 --> 00:38:10.002
Well, thank you, Charlie, for the introduction.

630
00:38:10.842 --> 00:38:14.682
And also thanks to Mike, in the first place many years

631
00:38:14.722 --> 00:38:18.202
ago, for asking me to be involved in the Mutagrass project, which you've

632
00:38:18.962 --> 00:38:19.722
just heard about.

633
00:38:20.642 --> 00:38:24.282
So I'm representing the team PROMINENT, and the acronym stands

634
00:38:24.322 --> 00:38:28.262
for Studies of Promotion to Inform Prevention.

635
00:38:28.542 --> 00:38:31.612
So as Paul Brennan came up with that title, I think it fits

636
00:38:32.742 --> 00:38:33.282
rather well.

637
00:38:34.982 --> 00:38:38.822
I first want to thank the Cancer Grand Challenges team

638
00:38:38.902 --> 00:38:40.212
for everything they've done

639
00:38:41.542 --> 00:38:44.782
to set up this whole program, which has really been, for me,

640
00:38:44.902 --> 00:38:47.002
transformative, liberating in many ways.

641
00:38:48.722 --> 00:38:52.522
But also the CRUK, who funded our work many

642
00:38:52.562 --> 00:38:56.282
years ago, and the NCI, who funded the other half of the work for many

643
00:38:56.322 --> 00:39:00.202
years. So, this is a long connection with both of those

644
00:39:00.762 --> 00:39:04.282
funding bodies over many decades, more decades than I care to remember.

645
00:39:06.722 --> 00:39:07.162
The

646
00:39:08.262 --> 00:39:12.002
topic that PROMINENT is working on is how does the

647
00:39:12.042 --> 00:39:16.022
environment influence cancer, and what can we do about it?

648
00:39:17.782 --> 00:39:21.621
When you look in the newspapers or you open up

649
00:39:21.681 --> 00:39:25.631
your iPhone these days, there's always something new about this

650
00:39:25.662 --> 00:39:29.282
compound or that chemical or this thing in the environment

651
00:39:29.342 --> 00:39:33.062
that's causing cancer. You heard from Mike about

652
00:39:33.122 --> 00:39:36.162
the increasing incidence of early onset colon cancer.

653
00:39:36.222 --> 00:39:37.762
We don't know what those causes are.

654
00:39:38.422 --> 00:39:42.362
And this slide has a whole list of possible risk factors

655
00:39:42.462 --> 00:39:43.642
from the environment,

656
00:39:44.742 --> 00:39:45.982
lifestyle factors,

657
00:39:46.922 --> 00:39:50.182
endogenous processes. Aging is a very important

658
00:39:51.022 --> 00:39:52.922
association with cancer.

659
00:39:54.622 --> 00:39:58.482
The problem is that we don't know which of these really are the main causes, which

660
00:39:58.502 --> 00:40:01.202
are the main drivers of the whole process of

661
00:40:02.042 --> 00:40:05.962
mutation and clonal selection. So we need to study these in

662
00:40:06.022 --> 00:40:09.742
great detail and find ways to monitor them, to test them,

663
00:40:10.222 --> 00:40:14.062
to quantify their roles, and be much more

664
00:40:14.142 --> 00:40:17.501
quantitative in our assessments of what these risk factors actually are.

665
00:40:19.142 --> 00:40:22.622
Superimposed on all of this, of course, is genetic background.

666
00:40:22.922 --> 00:40:26.382
We're all unique individuals with our own

667
00:40:27.142 --> 00:40:30.722
set of polymorphisms that we've inherited, and these genetic

668
00:40:30.742 --> 00:40:34.402
backgrounds, they affect all of the things that you see on this slide.

669
00:40:34.482 --> 00:40:38.322
The propensity for

670
00:40:38.362 --> 00:40:41.822
responding to a carcinogen can depend on metabolism.

671
00:40:42.322 --> 00:40:45.162
It can depend on many things, transport,

672
00:40:46.042 --> 00:40:49.822
all of which can be influenced by our own polymorphism.

673
00:40:49.882 --> 00:40:53.602
So this is something hovering in the background that we really,

674
00:40:54.302 --> 00:40:55.822
within PROMINENT, we're not

675
00:40:56.822 --> 00:41:00.662
looking at this in great detail, but it's a major feature that we

676
00:41:00.682 --> 00:41:03.442
need to take into consideration in the future.

677
00:41:04.062 --> 00:41:07.742
So the role of the environment in cancer, of course, goes back hundreds of years.

678
00:41:08.162 --> 00:41:10.502
This is something that many of you, I'm sure, have seen.

679
00:41:11.302 --> 00:41:15.222
Percival Pott in the 18th century found that chimney

680
00:41:15.302 --> 00:41:18.282
sweeps had a high incidence of scrotal cancer.

681
00:41:19.582 --> 00:41:23.522
A hundred and fifty years or so later, Yamagiwa

682
00:41:23.582 --> 00:41:27.462
and Ichikawa, they did the causal, the Koch's postulate type

683
00:41:27.522 --> 00:41:31.462
experiment. They took the coal tar, and they treated

684
00:41:31.862 --> 00:41:34.642
rabbits on the ears with coal tar repeatedly.

685
00:41:35.082 --> 00:41:38.522
Those rabbits got cancer. So that was the first causal link

686
00:41:38.562 --> 00:41:42.402
between exposure to anything, basically, and increasing

687
00:41:42.482 --> 00:41:43.182
cancer risk.

688
00:41:44.362 --> 00:41:47.642
That ear that got the cancer is still in the museum in Tokyo.

689
00:41:47.702 --> 00:41:50.862
You can visit it and see it if you feel so inclined.

690
00:41:52.742 --> 00:41:56.422
Thirty years after those experiments, in the 1940s,

691
00:41:57.082 --> 00:42:00.982
the group that Charlie mentioned in his introduction, Bern Bloom

692
00:42:01.002 --> 00:42:04.262
and Shubik, they did the first studies on trying to

693
00:42:04.702 --> 00:42:08.522
separate environmental carcinogenesis into different stages.

694
00:42:09.802 --> 00:42:12.922
And they used the coal tar that also gave the rabbit

695
00:42:14.502 --> 00:42:15.122
carcinoma.

696
00:42:16.422 --> 00:42:20.342
But what they showed was that coal tar in low doses as

697
00:42:20.382 --> 00:42:24.002
a single treatment did nothing. If you treat the mice with coal tar

698
00:42:24.602 --> 00:42:27.702
and wait for a whole year, they got no tumors.

699
00:42:28.222 --> 00:42:31.562
Similarly, if you treated them with an agent that caused inflammation and

700
00:42:31.602 --> 00:42:35.582
irritation on the skin, also the mice did not get any

701
00:42:35.622 --> 00:42:39.282
tumors. But in the third line here down, if you

702
00:42:40.122 --> 00:42:43.492
did the coal tar first and then chronic exposure to

703
00:42:43.522 --> 00:42:46.382
inflammation, then lots of tumors came up.

704
00:42:46.422 --> 00:42:50.362
The mice got benign tumors literally in a few weeks, and they developed

705
00:42:50.382 --> 00:42:54.362
malignant tumors in a couple of months, a few months, and that killed them.

706
00:42:55.662 --> 00:42:59.302
The order was important. If you do all that chronic inflammation

707
00:42:59.462 --> 00:43:02.022
first and then the coal tar, you don't get the tumors.

708
00:43:02.062 --> 00:43:05.682
It has to be coal tar first, followed by mutations.

709
00:43:06.582 --> 00:43:08.022
This bottom line here

710
00:43:09.542 --> 00:43:12.512
is a very important experiment that Bern Bloom and Shubik did,

711
00:43:13.262 --> 00:43:17.122
which really introduced, I think, another dimension to the whole discussion

712
00:43:17.162 --> 00:43:21.146
about mutations versusNo, I shouldn't say versus mutations,

713
00:43:21.206 --> 00:43:24.446
in addition to inflammation and how these work together.

714
00:43:25.266 --> 00:43:29.026
What they showed was that the promotion step, in other words, the inflammation,

715
00:43:29.446 --> 00:43:31.206
was actually the rate-limiting step.

716
00:43:32.346 --> 00:43:36.186
You could do a single treatment with the coal tar and then wait

717
00:43:36.246 --> 00:43:37.826
until the mouse is almost dead,

718
00:43:38.686 --> 00:43:42.366
18 months, and then begin the promoter treatment, the inflammation

719
00:43:42.446 --> 00:43:45.486
treatment, and the tumors came up within a few weeks.

720
00:43:45.566 --> 00:43:49.326
So those, whatever was happening by with coal tar, that was permanent.

721
00:43:50.346 --> 00:43:53.646
And those cells sit there for the life of the mice, don't do anything, but when

722
00:43:53.666 --> 00:43:54.886
they're exposed to

723
00:43:55.766 --> 00:43:59.026
a neurotoxin for just a short time, then they begin to expand.

724
00:43:59.746 --> 00:43:59.946
So

725
00:44:01.466 --> 00:44:05.226
this now, I'm going to run through this quickly because I don't want to go

726
00:44:05.586 --> 00:44:06.066
too much,

727
00:44:06.946 --> 00:44:08.246
or at all over my time.

728
00:44:10.166 --> 00:44:12.786
So going from the early stuff from Pot,

729
00:44:13.906 --> 00:44:17.406
there's a huge amount of work done over the decades by many

730
00:44:17.786 --> 00:44:21.086
different groups. Kennaway found the important

731
00:44:21.126 --> 00:44:22.866
constituents in the coal tar.

732
00:44:24.365 --> 00:44:27.986
The Millers showed that these constituents, these chemicals, they require

733
00:44:28.026 --> 00:44:31.546
metabolic activation. They just don't get into cells and do stuff.

734
00:44:31.606 --> 00:44:34.526
They need to be metabolically activated.

735
00:44:34.766 --> 00:44:38.386
Charlie Heidelberg has showed that they can form or do form direct

736
00:44:38.486 --> 00:44:42.366
adducts with the DNA. They stick onto the DNA, and that's what causes

737
00:44:42.406 --> 00:44:44.026
the ultimate mutations.

738
00:44:45.046 --> 00:44:48.866
We got into this in the early '80s by taking some of these mutagens

739
00:44:49.346 --> 00:44:52.806
and showing that they cause specific kinds of mutations in animal models.

740
00:44:53.666 --> 00:44:57.266
And that, of course, was taken to another dimension in the work that you've just

741
00:44:57.306 --> 00:45:01.106
heard about from Mike, in the early '20s.

742
00:45:01.866 --> 00:45:05.266
How they developed this concept of mutational signatures,

743
00:45:05.726 --> 00:45:08.406
which has really transformed our understanding of how

744
00:45:09.566 --> 00:45:13.546
these carcinogens are distributed throughout the world and contribute to

745
00:45:13.606 --> 00:45:15.286
many thousands of cancer types.

746
00:45:16.786 --> 00:45:18.426
We also need to think about promotion.

747
00:45:19.626 --> 00:45:23.366
The inflammation connection to cancer, of course, goes

748
00:45:23.426 --> 00:45:26.366
back again, Virchow back in

749
00:45:26.426 --> 00:45:29.706
1855, and many other people since then.

750
00:45:29.726 --> 00:45:32.726
The slide space isn't big enough to acknowledge everything.

751
00:45:33.326 --> 00:45:37.086
The Bernblum and Shubik experiment, we've already many mentioned, but

752
00:45:37.506 --> 00:45:41.386
it has to be remembered that in the '50s and '60s,

753
00:45:42.026 --> 00:45:45.826
these promotion experiments, inflammation and promotion, were carried out with

754
00:45:46.266 --> 00:45:50.086
what we now know are very potent mutagens: tobacco, cigarette

755
00:45:50.166 --> 00:45:51.446
smoke, and air pollution.

756
00:45:52.306 --> 00:45:55.686
They have both promoting activity as well as mutagenic activity.

757
00:45:56.046 --> 00:45:57.426
And I think this is an important

758
00:45:58.466 --> 00:46:01.666
component that we have to think about, is these are

759
00:46:01.726 --> 00:46:05.626
interacting all the time in complex ways that we really don't

760
00:46:05.666 --> 00:46:06.326
understand.

761
00:46:07.846 --> 00:46:10.786
It's not just like a mouse experiment where you have a constant dose.

762
00:46:11.566 --> 00:46:15.346
There's variable dose levels, various combinations are involved

763
00:46:15.406 --> 00:46:18.206
in exposures in human populations.

764
00:46:19.046 --> 00:46:21.926
Hecker was the guy I did my postdoc with.

765
00:46:22.446 --> 00:46:25.426
He found TPA, which is the quintessential tumor promoter.

766
00:46:26.146 --> 00:46:29.826
Sugimura extended this whole field by showing that you can have

767
00:46:29.886 --> 00:46:33.726
completely different types of promoters that have different mechanisms of action.

768
00:46:35.606 --> 00:46:36.466
The promotion work

769
00:46:37.446 --> 00:46:40.846
was in its heyday in the '70s, '80s, and '90s.

770
00:46:41.406 --> 00:46:44.526
This is a group in Heidelberg I worked with.

771
00:46:44.966 --> 00:46:48.286
In the US, there were many groups working on mechanisms of promotion.

772
00:46:48.326 --> 00:46:51.826
But all of that kind of tailed off in the '80s when

773
00:46:51.866 --> 00:46:55.416
mutations came along. We all shifted to look at mutations,

774
00:46:56.866 --> 00:47:00.146
including my own lab. We switched and did a lot of work then on

775
00:47:00.346 --> 00:47:04.246
mutations. But now what I was told for this is I have to talk

776
00:47:04.306 --> 00:47:07.786
about how mutations and inflammation conspire together.

777
00:47:07.866 --> 00:47:09.726
So that was the title I was given for the talk.

778
00:47:11.706 --> 00:47:15.506
So we went back a few years ago and repeated the original Bernblum

779
00:47:15.566 --> 00:47:18.666
experiment to see, are they right?

780
00:47:18.766 --> 00:47:21.086
Were they right that the initiation event was

781
00:47:22.406 --> 00:47:25.646
permanent? First of all, in the 1980s, we had actually

782
00:47:25.746 --> 00:47:28.766
identified the initiation event for this model.

783
00:47:29.426 --> 00:47:32.746
It's a specific mutation, an A-to-T mutation

784
00:47:32.866 --> 00:47:35.286
in codon 61 of Ras,

785
00:47:36.606 --> 00:47:40.466
and that's because the DMBA binds to adenosines, and it causes an

786
00:47:40.546 --> 00:47:43.216
A-to-T mutation. So that gives us a mutational signature.

787
00:47:43.906 --> 00:47:46.286
At that point, this was a single nucleotide signature.

788
00:47:46.706 --> 00:47:50.546
This has now, of course, been extended to trinucleotide and pentanucleotide

789
00:47:50.606 --> 00:47:54.366
signatures. But we could look for that mutational signature in

790
00:47:54.406 --> 00:47:58.326
tumors that were induced by this carcinogen, and that's what you see on the

791
00:47:58.366 --> 00:48:00.366
bottom part of this slide.

792
00:48:02.086 --> 00:48:05.646
The Y-axis here are mutation numbers in

793
00:48:05.766 --> 00:48:09.586
individual carcinomas from these mice, all skin tumors.

794
00:48:11.246 --> 00:48:14.606
And some of them, as you can see, have 30,000 mutations,

795
00:48:15.306 --> 00:48:18.906
up to 50,000 mutations. The purple is the

796
00:48:18.946 --> 00:48:22.906
DMBA signature. So that means that these bars, since

797
00:48:22.966 --> 00:48:26.746
initiation is on one day, all of the mutations are caused on that

798
00:48:26.846 --> 00:48:30.746
one day or within a week of that first

799
00:48:30.806 --> 00:48:34.126
exposure. So it's a snapshot in time of

800
00:48:34.166 --> 00:48:36.926
how many mutations that single dose of

801
00:48:36.986 --> 00:48:40.006
DMBA can actually cause.

802
00:48:41.746 --> 00:48:45.486
And what it says is that on the right, where it says standard, that's the

803
00:48:45.506 --> 00:48:49.186
classic model. You take young mice, you treat them once with DMBA,

804
00:48:49.766 --> 00:48:53.346
stimulate them with inflammatory agents, TPA in this case,

805
00:48:54.126 --> 00:48:55.526
get the tumors, and sequence them.

806
00:48:55.686 --> 00:48:59.446
And there's a lot of variability in the number of DMBA-induced

807
00:48:59.506 --> 00:49:03.346
mutations. But they all have exactly the same initiating mutations,

808
00:49:03.426 --> 00:49:05.686
which is that HRAS thing I showed earlier.

809
00:49:06.766 --> 00:49:10.286
So that is the one common factor. All the other mutations

810
00:49:10.346 --> 00:49:11.386
are optional.

811
00:49:13.046 --> 00:49:16.766
When we did the Bernblum experiment with the delay, which is on the left

812
00:49:16.826 --> 00:49:17.086
here,

813
00:49:18.306 --> 00:49:22.046
there was no difference in the numbers or the types of mutations compared to the

814
00:49:22.126 --> 00:49:23.926
standard model, so they were right.

815
00:49:24.046 --> 00:49:28.026
This tumor hereThat has the almost 50,000 mutations.

816
00:49:28.126 --> 00:49:32.006
That was sitting in a mouse skin for almost a year and didn't do anything,

817
00:49:32.226 --> 00:49:36.126
but then it gave tumors a few weeks after we started the

818
00:49:36.136 --> 00:49:38.956
promotion experiment. So they were absolutely spot on.

819
00:49:39.886 --> 00:49:43.486
They did speculate at that time that this was a mutational event.

820
00:49:43.526 --> 00:49:47.446
Of course, we didn't know what the structure of DNA was then, so I don't know

821
00:49:47.486 --> 00:49:49.246
how they managed to come to that conclusion.

822
00:49:49.286 --> 00:49:52.546
But they said this was a mutational event, and they were

823
00:49:52.626 --> 00:49:55.046
absolutely correct in assuming that.

824
00:49:56.246 --> 00:49:59.126
This is the experiment you already saw from Mike,

825
00:49:59.866 --> 00:50:03.746
showing that mutations are an

826
00:50:03.766 --> 00:50:07.306
important feature of many chemicals that are in the

827
00:50:07.326 --> 00:50:10.666
environment. But what this slide shows, and Mike

828
00:50:10.886 --> 00:50:14.726
emphasized, is that the vast majority of

829
00:50:15.446 --> 00:50:18.806
chemicals that the National Toxicology Program and

830
00:50:18.906 --> 00:50:22.716
IARC have classified as being potential carcinogens,

831
00:50:22.866 --> 00:50:25.926
they are not mutagenic as far as we can tell.

832
00:50:27.826 --> 00:50:30.965
Only two or three out of the 20 that were

833
00:50:31.306 --> 00:50:33.666
assessed showed any mutational signatures.

834
00:50:33.746 --> 00:50:36.086
All of the others looked exactly like spontaneous

835
00:50:37.506 --> 00:50:39.326
tumors, the same numbers of mutations,

836
00:50:41.766 --> 00:50:43.086
the same types of mutations.

837
00:50:45.806 --> 00:50:46.006
So,

838
00:50:46.926 --> 00:50:50.846
this takes me on to the work in Prominent, the more recent work, a

839
00:50:51.486 --> 00:50:53.906
scientific vignette, just to finish off.

840
00:50:54.426 --> 00:50:56.676
So what we've been trying to do within Prominent is

841
00:50:57.526 --> 00:50:59.786
go back to the beginnings and look at where the

842
00:51:00.766 --> 00:51:04.706
initiating mutations are, which cells are they in, how many are there,

843
00:51:04.726 --> 00:51:08.146
and how do they respond to promoters? Do different promoters do different things?

844
00:51:09.166 --> 00:51:11.546
Do they have a common mechanism of action?

845
00:51:12.406 --> 00:51:16.086
So here you have a diagram. This is

846
00:51:16.106 --> 00:51:18.666
taken from a recent review. Nuria

847
00:51:19.466 --> 00:51:21.246
Lopez-Bigas, who I think is here.

848
00:51:23.946 --> 00:51:27.766
We conspired together, the Prominent team, and wrote this review on promotion.

849
00:51:27.846 --> 00:51:31.626
So anything that you miss in the next few slides, you'll find in

850
00:51:31.686 --> 00:51:32.326
that review.

851
00:51:33.446 --> 00:51:37.286
So the idea is that we can identify single mutated

852
00:51:37.366 --> 00:51:38.806
cells, as shown by these colored

853
00:51:40.246 --> 00:51:43.046
hexagons in an epithelial tissue.

854
00:51:43.606 --> 00:51:47.566
When we treat with TPA, some of those specific mutant cells will

855
00:51:47.686 --> 00:51:51.586
clonally expand, and if the purple cells clonally expand

856
00:51:51.626 --> 00:51:54.146
enough, then they will give us a tumor.

857
00:51:55.646 --> 00:51:59.586
There are, however, other sources of mutations in all of our

858
00:51:59.606 --> 00:52:00.386
normal tissues,

859
00:52:01.866 --> 00:52:05.686
and they could be carcinogen induced or they could be

860
00:52:05.726 --> 00:52:06.606
spontaneous.

861
00:52:08.406 --> 00:52:11.726
And if they are spontaneous, then maybe they respond.

862
00:52:11.846 --> 00:52:15.106
Maybe the red clones respond to TPA, and they'll give us a red

863
00:52:15.116 --> 00:52:18.866
tumor. If the tissue is exposed to a different

864
00:52:18.876 --> 00:52:21.946
type of promoter, like wounding or PFAS,

865
00:52:22.866 --> 00:52:26.166
other chemicals that are very good candidate promoters,

866
00:52:26.726 --> 00:52:28.886
then maybe they will select a different clone.

867
00:52:28.926 --> 00:52:32.366
And I think that's a theme that's emerging from many of the studies we're now

868
00:52:32.406 --> 00:52:35.746
doing, is that these selective constraints are very specific.

869
00:52:35.786 --> 00:52:39.686
There's a zoo of mutations and mutant clones in our tissues, all of our

870
00:52:39.746 --> 00:52:43.666
normal tissues, and they're responding in very different ways to what we eat, what

871
00:52:43.726 --> 00:52:45.866
we drink, what we're exposed to.

872
00:52:48.606 --> 00:52:52.226
The workhorse tool for analyzing these

873
00:52:52.246 --> 00:52:55.826
mutations, which are very rare mutations in normal tissues, was

874
00:52:55.906 --> 00:52:59.506
developed by Jesse Salk and his company, TwinStrand, which

875
00:52:59.586 --> 00:53:02.046
unfortunately has now, I think, gone out of business.

876
00:53:03.386 --> 00:53:07.055
But it's an amazingly efficient way to look at really,

877
00:53:07.166 --> 00:53:11.106
really rare mutations in single cells and

878
00:53:11.146 --> 00:53:15.086
in tissues. So we've been using this extensively with a lot of

879
00:53:15.126 --> 00:53:16.566
help from Nuria's team,

880
00:53:17.726 --> 00:53:21.406
to develop our own process now for going through this, since the

881
00:53:21.666 --> 00:53:25.006
company has gone out of business. So I just want to quickly take you through what

882
00:53:25.386 --> 00:53:29.296
we've been seeing with this very deep sequencing approach, where you're hunting

883
00:53:29.326 --> 00:53:32.346
for rare mutant cells in these normal

884
00:53:32.966 --> 00:53:36.866
tissues. So this box up at the top here, these

885
00:53:36.886 --> 00:53:40.286
pink boxes, each box represents one mouse.

886
00:53:41.326 --> 00:53:45.266
And this is looking for mutations in RAS genes, NRAS,

887
00:53:45.326 --> 00:53:48.586
KRAS, and HRAS, those three very famous RAS genes.

888
00:53:48.946 --> 00:53:49.886
And the top panel,

889
00:53:50.746 --> 00:53:53.066
these are controls. These are young mice.

890
00:53:53.306 --> 00:53:57.186
There are 10 mice there. Five of them have mutations, five of

891
00:53:57.226 --> 00:54:00.826
them do not have mutations. And that's the kind of statistics we see.

892
00:54:01.046 --> 00:54:02.806
We take the DNA, we do deep sequencing.

893
00:54:02.926 --> 00:54:04.786
Sometimes we find some of these mutant cells.

894
00:54:05.746 --> 00:54:07.386
But what you can see is that

895
00:54:08.366 --> 00:54:10.006
within those three RAS genes,

896
00:54:11.586 --> 00:54:14.986
there's... This pointer I don't think is working here, actually.

897
00:54:17.126 --> 00:54:18.786
No, it's not. Anyway.

898
00:54:22.186 --> 00:54:23.676
Yeah. Within these three RAS genes,

899
00:54:24.686 --> 00:54:28.666
several of the boxes have a KRAS G12D mutation, which is

900
00:54:28.706 --> 00:54:31.606
one of the most common mutations found in human cancers.

901
00:54:32.166 --> 00:54:34.886
Several others have a KRAS G13R mutation.

902
00:54:35.426 --> 00:54:39.166
These are very common mutations for some unknown

903
00:54:39.206 --> 00:54:43.186
reason in normal mouse tissues. Both of those mutations come up

904
00:54:43.286 --> 00:54:43.966
repeatedly.

905
00:54:45.206 --> 00:54:49.166
And when we add the DMBA on the middle set of panels

906
00:54:49.226 --> 00:54:51.426
there, then you can begin to see

907
00:54:52.826 --> 00:54:54.946
the codon 61 mutations that all come.

908
00:54:54.986 --> 00:54:58.566
There's a whole bunch of different codon 61 mutations that you can now see

909
00:54:58.986 --> 00:55:01.586
a week after that single treatment with the DMBA.

910
00:55:02.066 --> 00:55:04.186
So these are the classic initiating mutations.

911
00:55:04.786 --> 00:55:08.466
We see codon 61 in HRAS, KRAS, and

912
00:55:08.626 --> 00:55:12.606
NRAS. But then when we treat those with the promoter TPA,

913
00:55:13.206 --> 00:55:15.906
the biggest pink circles are HRAS Q61L.

914
00:55:16.346 --> 00:55:20.066
So those are the mutations that we find in the actual tumors from this model.

915
00:55:20.586 --> 00:55:22.886
The other mutations are there. They're all very

916
00:55:24.166 --> 00:55:28.126
strong, well-characterized RAS mutations, but they do not respond

917
00:55:28.166 --> 00:55:30.626
to this particular promoter very well.

918
00:55:31.646 --> 00:55:34.506
The one that comes through is the HRAS Q61L.

919
00:55:35.066 --> 00:55:38.166
But just a quick word about these spontaneous mutations, because I think it's

920
00:55:38.206 --> 00:55:41.246
relevant also to some of the work that Mike talked about.

921
00:55:41.746 --> 00:55:43.306
We all have spontaneous mutations.

922
00:55:43.346 --> 00:55:47.216
We tend to think of them as being random.New mistakes in

923
00:55:47.296 --> 00:55:50.376
DNA repair during DNA replication.

924
00:55:50.456 --> 00:55:54.356
These two I mentioned, G12D and G13R, are very common.

925
00:55:54.396 --> 00:55:58.036
They do respond to TPA. You see these big pink circles for

926
00:55:58.156 --> 00:56:02.146
G12. These are all independent mice, and that shows all of

927
00:56:02.176 --> 00:56:04.556
the mutations in those mice, not just those ones.

928
00:56:05.836 --> 00:56:09.676
But when you look over time, what we find is that on the

929
00:56:09.736 --> 00:56:13.576
right panel there, if you look at the KRAS G12D, that's TPA

930
00:56:13.636 --> 00:56:17.496
alone. The blue intensity shows those mutations are increasing with TPA.

931
00:56:18.195 --> 00:56:20.996
But then the next two squares are white.

932
00:56:21.156 --> 00:56:24.826
That means they've disappeared. So if you wait for another four weeks, they've

933
00:56:24.876 --> 00:56:25.205
gone.

934
00:56:26.136 --> 00:56:29.596
So basically what we find is that these spontaneous

935
00:56:29.636 --> 00:56:33.416
mutations do respond initially to the promoter, but then they crash

936
00:56:33.516 --> 00:56:37.136
out and they disappear. And we don't know why they disappear or how they disappear,

937
00:56:37.836 --> 00:56:41.776
but they do. And if you then, on the right-hand panel, is a

938
00:56:41.796 --> 00:56:45.616
DMBA-initiated set of mutations in all three

939
00:56:45.676 --> 00:56:49.536
RAS genes. You can see the strongest blue line is opposite HRAS

940
00:56:49.636 --> 00:56:53.576
Q61L. That's the one that goes up and keeps going up and gives you

941
00:56:53.616 --> 00:56:57.376
the tumor. But you can also see that the KRAS G13R on the

942
00:56:57.416 --> 00:57:01.076
right-hand panel is this intense blue signal there, too.

943
00:57:01.116 --> 00:57:04.916
So that is responding very well, even after DMBA to

944
00:57:04.956 --> 00:57:08.896
promotion. But again, it crashes out, and it never gives you a tumor

945
00:57:08.936 --> 00:57:12.256
under those circumstances. What we have, however, found

946
00:57:13.376 --> 00:57:16.576
is that, so these green bars here, this is the KRAS

947
00:57:16.636 --> 00:57:20.576
G13R, which has turned out to be very fascinating.

948
00:57:21.136 --> 00:57:23.836
It goes up in response to short-term TPA

949
00:57:24.816 --> 00:57:27.526
in non-initiated mice and also in initiated mice.

950
00:57:27.596 --> 00:57:30.636
It goes up, but in both cases, if you keep going, it disappears.

951
00:57:31.236 --> 00:57:35.196
So those mutant cells do not ever give us any tumors in wild-type

952
00:57:35.236 --> 00:57:35.636
mice.

953
00:57:36.476 --> 00:57:39.856
But if we generate HRAS knockout mice,

954
00:57:40.496 --> 00:57:43.636
then we get lots of tumors with those two specific mutations.

955
00:57:44.596 --> 00:57:48.536
So those are spontaneous mutations, which are revealed when you knock out

956
00:57:48.576 --> 00:57:52.376
the competing HRAS gene. And this whole field of

957
00:57:52.416 --> 00:57:53.176
competition

958
00:57:54.356 --> 00:57:58.336
goes back to Hinis Murata in Drosophila many years

959
00:57:58.376 --> 00:58:01.196
ago, showing how different clones of cells compete with each other

960
00:58:02.096 --> 00:58:05.676
for space, for nutrients, for survival

961
00:58:06.056 --> 00:58:06.876
in these tissues.

962
00:58:07.756 --> 00:58:10.816
So this is an experiment with the HRAS knockout mice.

963
00:58:12.616 --> 00:58:16.376
And what you can see is the green bar shows these are HRAS knockout

964
00:58:16.396 --> 00:58:18.336
mice treated chronically with TPA.

965
00:58:19.116 --> 00:58:22.716
And across the bottom on the right, those mice get very, very

966
00:58:22.896 --> 00:58:25.456
few tumors compared to the wild-type mice.

967
00:58:25.736 --> 00:58:28.776
But the tumors they do get have that bright green signal.

968
00:58:29.176 --> 00:58:32.516
Those are KRAS G13R mutations. That's not a

969
00:58:32.616 --> 00:58:35.876
mutation that's caused by DMBA. It doesn't have the

970
00:58:35.916 --> 00:58:39.806
signature. It's spontaneous. But nevertheless, it's selected

971
00:58:39.816 --> 00:58:41.696
by this whole process.

972
00:58:43.696 --> 00:58:47.676
So this, I think, helps us to understand some of the data

973
00:58:47.736 --> 00:58:51.176
that have been very confusing, at least to us, over the years.

974
00:58:52.156 --> 00:58:55.676
On the left, there are several papers from the group of Valentina

975
00:58:55.756 --> 00:58:56.316
Greco,

976
00:58:57.856 --> 00:58:59.976
who has followed on this

977
00:59:01.236 --> 00:59:05.196
idea started by Murata about cell-cell competition.

978
00:59:05.236 --> 00:59:09.056
And she has looked at competition between different clones in normal

979
00:59:09.136 --> 00:59:13.056
tissue. And she has shown very elegantly that if

980
00:59:13.136 --> 00:59:15.356
you induce mutations genetically

981
00:59:16.176 --> 00:59:20.016
in KRAS or HRAS, so you have a lot of mutations driven

982
00:59:20.076 --> 00:59:23.096
genetically by tissue-specific promoters,

983
00:59:24.976 --> 00:59:27.296
you should get loads of cancers, but you don't.

984
00:59:27.936 --> 00:59:31.216
And they've shown that the normal cells outcompete

985
00:59:31.276 --> 00:59:35.236
the RAS mutant cells in these tissues.

986
00:59:35.896 --> 00:59:39.796
I never understood it because the paper on the right is the one that I

987
00:59:39.836 --> 00:59:43.416
showed you earlier, which clearly shows that the RAS mutations sit there for a

988
00:59:43.456 --> 00:59:46.636
year. They're definitely not outcompeted by the normal cells.

989
00:59:47.016 --> 00:59:50.976
It turns out these are two different categories of mutations and probably

990
00:59:51.016 --> 00:59:54.796
in two different cell types. We don't fully understand this yet.

991
00:59:56.876 --> 01:00:00.776
So this whole idea about clonal competition is

992
01:00:00.816 --> 01:00:03.475
going on in all of us all the time, but I think there

993
01:00:04.636 --> 01:00:07.256
is a huge amount that we still have to understand.

994
01:00:08.416 --> 01:00:12.376
We're taking a number of approaches within Prominent to look at ways

995
01:00:12.516 --> 01:00:15.976
to monitor these processes and

996
01:00:16.056 --> 01:00:19.896
understand these processes and ultimately to try to prevent

997
01:00:19.936 --> 01:00:23.276
these processes. I'm sure I've gone over time, so I'm going to stop here.

998
01:00:23.876 --> 01:00:27.536
These are the people who've been doing all of this work over the

999
01:00:27.576 --> 01:00:30.536
years. On the left is the larger Prominent team.

1000
01:00:30.556 --> 01:00:33.876
Paul Brennan is over on the left here.

1001
01:00:34.616 --> 01:00:37.556
Nuria is in the middle somewhere. Yes, there she is there.

1002
01:00:37.616 --> 01:00:41.016
She's about 10th from the right. I should have put an arrow on

1003
01:00:41.056 --> 01:00:45.036
there. Nuria and Paul are the co-leaders of the

1004
01:00:45.076 --> 01:00:48.916
team. Nuria has a beautiful paper which has just come out, I think, in

1005
01:00:48.976 --> 01:00:49.376
Nature,

1006
01:00:50.336 --> 01:00:53.746
using all of these same technologies but to look at human bladder cancer

1007
01:00:54.276 --> 01:00:57.336
and has identified TERT promoter mutations

1008
01:00:58.616 --> 01:01:02.216
that are directly linked to cigarette smoking, but this is in bladder.

1009
01:01:03.056 --> 01:01:06.936
So very, very interesting work. I'd recommend that you go and read that paper.

1010
01:01:07.556 --> 01:01:10.956
The others on the right, this is the core group at UCSF.

1011
01:01:11.056 --> 01:01:14.456
Eve Kandiba has done much of the clonal selection work,

1012
01:01:15.396 --> 01:01:15.976
helped by

1013
01:01:17.096 --> 01:01:19.456
Andrea Cortabi and many of the others here.

1014
01:01:19.496 --> 01:01:22.336
And I'd like to thank again the Cancer Research team

1015
01:01:23.196 --> 01:01:25.476
for all of their support over the years. Thank you.

1016
01:01:34.736 --> 01:01:35.376
Thank you, Alan.

1017
01:01:36.616 --> 01:01:40.456
Again, we'll have questions right at the end. So next we have Karen Kochowski.

1018
01:01:41.256 --> 01:01:44.976
Karen is a professor at Brigham and Women's Hospital, Harvard Medical School.

1019
01:01:45.856 --> 01:01:49.796
Her research focuses on deconstructing the pathogenesis of

1020
01:01:49.876 --> 01:01:52.016
RAS-related signaling pathways in cancer.

1021
01:01:52.776 --> 01:01:55.996
She's been a central member of the Specify Cancer team that seeks to

1022
01:01:56.056 --> 01:01:59.716
understand why specific oncogenic drivers occur

1023
01:01:59.756 --> 01:02:02.636
in some tissues, some tumor types, but not others.

1024
01:02:02.676 --> 01:02:06.596
A really central question to understanding signal transduction across organ

1025
01:02:06.696 --> 01:02:09.746
sites and their role in cancer initiation and

1026
01:02:09.856 --> 01:02:13.657
maintenance.So she's been studying the intersection between oncogenic and

1027
01:02:13.708 --> 01:02:17.648
epigenetic signals in cancer and investigating how convergent

1028
01:02:17.688 --> 01:02:21.648
points represent new and unique nodes of

1029
01:02:21.688 --> 01:02:25.078
vulnerability. She's published some really elegant work showing how

1030
01:02:25.128 --> 01:02:28.538
combinations of inhibitors such as EZH2,

1031
01:02:28.968 --> 01:02:32.368
AKT inhibitors, can rewire triple-negative breast cancer cells

1032
01:02:32.408 --> 01:02:36.228
and differentiate them into sort of more luminal progenitors that become

1033
01:02:36.238 --> 01:02:39.958
sensitive to both treatments. I'm sure she'll discuss similar such work

1034
01:02:39.988 --> 01:02:42.548
today, funded from Specify Cancer,

1035
01:02:43.487 --> 01:02:47.028
and it's been really a phenomenally successful grand challenge

1036
01:02:47.328 --> 01:02:49.368
in collaboration with Steve Elledge.

1037
01:02:50.008 --> 01:02:53.868
She's received the Translational Science Award of the Children's

1038
01:02:54.068 --> 01:02:57.548
Tumor Foundation, the Innovative Research Idea Prize,

1039
01:02:58.008 --> 01:03:01.608
and amongst others, the National Neurofibromatosis Foundation

1040
01:03:01.688 --> 01:03:05.268
Prize, and several other accolades I haven't got time to say today.

1041
01:03:05.528 --> 01:03:07.408
Karen, welcome. Thank you very much.

1042
01:03:27.288 --> 01:03:30.868
Great. Thank you very much. I would just like to thank the

1043
01:03:30.948 --> 01:03:34.628
organizers of this particular session for inviting me to present our work today.

1044
01:03:35.348 --> 01:03:39.288
But more importantly, I'd really like to thank the Cancer Research UK and the Mark

1045
01:03:39.348 --> 01:03:43.188
Foundation for funding our Specify Cancer Grand Challenge team.

1046
01:03:43.238 --> 01:03:46.948
And as you've heard from others, this has really been a transformative opportunity.

1047
01:03:52.548 --> 01:03:56.488
So, so far we've heard about how known and unknown carcinogens

1048
01:03:56.508 --> 01:03:59.438
and clonal expansion function in cancer promotion,

1049
01:04:00.308 --> 01:04:04.048
and I will now talk about how epigenetic events contribute to these

1050
01:04:04.088 --> 01:04:06.848
processes, and in particular, how epigenetic

1051
01:04:06.888 --> 01:04:10.128
defects cooperate with more classical

1052
01:04:10.168 --> 01:04:13.068
oncogenes to drive very tumor-specific and

1053
01:04:13.108 --> 01:04:16.798
tissue-specific biology. And moreover, how this

1054
01:04:16.808 --> 01:04:20.488
results in the development of therapeutic vulnerabilities that can be

1055
01:04:20.528 --> 01:04:21.428
readily targeted.

1056
01:04:26.888 --> 01:04:30.808
So by way of background, I was a PI on the Specify Cancer team

1057
01:04:30.888 --> 01:04:34.848
led by Steve Elledge, and our broad goal was to investigate

1058
01:04:34.908 --> 01:04:38.448
why specific oncogenes and tumor suppressors are so tumor-specific,

1059
01:04:38.968 --> 01:04:42.848
and second, to use this insight, as well as unbiased approaches,

1060
01:04:43.228 --> 01:04:46.768
to identify novel tissue-specific therapeutic vulnerabilities.

1061
01:04:49.188 --> 01:04:51.368
Our team focused on the RAS pathway,

1062
01:04:52.268 --> 01:04:56.148
the WNT pathway, the PRC2 complex, and also

1063
01:04:56.168 --> 01:04:59.488
employed broader genetic and computational

1064
01:04:59.528 --> 01:05:02.908
approaches to create tissue-specific maps of unique

1065
01:05:02.928 --> 01:05:05.488
drivers and therapeutic vulnerabilities.

1066
01:05:06.528 --> 01:05:10.028
Christian Helene and I specifically worked on understanding how

1067
01:05:10.068 --> 01:05:13.398
defects in this epigenetic complex, the PRC2 complex,

1068
01:05:13.768 --> 01:05:17.448
contributes to tumor development and progression, and more

1069
01:05:17.488 --> 01:05:21.108
broadly, how epigenetic alterations both permit and

1070
01:05:21.188 --> 01:05:24.728
reinforce the tissue-specific activity of these and other

1071
01:05:24.797 --> 01:05:26.028
oncogenic pathways.

1072
01:05:27.548 --> 01:05:31.228
And so because I was asked to speak about epigenetics, I

1073
01:05:31.268 --> 01:05:33.768
will limit my discussion today on that.

1074
01:05:35.328 --> 01:05:39.208
So if you think about it, epigenetic regulators are truly the guardians of tissue

1075
01:05:39.288 --> 01:05:41.988
specificity and perhaps oncogenesis in general.

1076
01:05:43.468 --> 01:05:47.218
Because while tumors contain alterations in many oncogenic drivers that

1077
01:05:47.228 --> 01:05:51.148
control cell signaling, for example, the ultimate

1078
01:05:51.208 --> 01:05:54.388
transcriptional output of any upstream oncogenic event

1079
01:05:55.408 --> 01:05:59.168
is largely dependent on the epigenetic state of a tissue, which can drive

1080
01:05:59.388 --> 01:06:03.268
either the amplification or the repression of specific transcriptional

1081
01:06:03.308 --> 01:06:07.268
responses. And so we thought that if we wanted to really understand the

1082
01:06:07.328 --> 01:06:11.248
tissue specificity of the PRC2 complex, we need to study

1083
01:06:11.288 --> 01:06:12.368
it in conjunction

1084
01:06:13.228 --> 01:06:15.268
with tissue-specific oncogenic drivers.

1085
01:06:17.598 --> 01:06:21.268
So in doing so, we decided to focus on breast cancer,

1086
01:06:21.328 --> 01:06:25.088
where PI3-kinase pathway mutations are highly enriched compared to

1087
01:06:25.148 --> 01:06:29.028
other tumor types. And so for example, 40% of

1088
01:06:29.328 --> 01:06:32.928
hormone receptor-positive luminal tumors harbor mutations in

1089
01:06:32.948 --> 01:06:33.758
PIK3CA.

1090
01:06:36.108 --> 01:06:39.728
And as such, PI3-kinase alpha-selective inhibitors and AKT

1091
01:06:39.768 --> 01:06:43.348
inhibitors have each been approved for the treatment of advanced hormone

1092
01:06:43.388 --> 01:06:44.888
receptor-positive disease.

1093
01:06:47.408 --> 01:06:51.328
However, these agents are not effect in triple-negative breast cancer, at least

1094
01:06:51.368 --> 01:06:53.168
when combined with chemotherapy.

1095
01:06:54.248 --> 01:06:58.098
But we wondered if perhaps these tumors might not be responding, not

1096
01:06:58.108 --> 01:07:01.708
because the PI3-kinase pathway isn't important, but because they're in a

1097
01:07:01.748 --> 01:07:05.688
less differentiated, more basal-like state as compared to these

1098
01:07:05.728 --> 01:07:07.508
ER-positive tumors.

1099
01:07:11.148 --> 01:07:14.688
And if so, perhaps we might be able to sensitize these tumors to AKT

1100
01:07:14.708 --> 01:07:18.048
inhibitors if we're able to shift them somehow to this more

1101
01:07:18.108 --> 01:07:19.268
luminal-like state,

1102
01:07:20.428 --> 01:07:23.528
which is what really led us to the PRC2 complex.

1103
01:07:24.608 --> 01:07:28.108
So the PRC2 complex, it drives histone H2K27

1104
01:07:28.148 --> 01:07:32.138
methylation, and through its catalytic component, EZH2,

1105
01:07:32.648 --> 01:07:36.478
silences specific genes, often those associated with differentiation.

1106
01:07:37.028 --> 01:07:40.868
And in fact, EZH2 is known to be broadly involved in stem cell maintenance.

1107
01:07:44.008 --> 01:07:47.728
Moreover, EZH2 and the PRC2 complex in general does play an

1108
01:07:47.748 --> 01:07:51.308
oncogenic role in a specific subset of cancers.

1109
01:07:51.588 --> 01:07:54.988
Gain-of-function mutations do occur in melanoma and lymphoma, for

1110
01:07:55.028 --> 01:07:58.888
example, but it is more frequently overexpressed in a small

1111
01:07:58.928 --> 01:08:02.168
subset of solid tumors, including breast, colon, and prostate.

1112
01:08:02.848 --> 01:08:06.808
In triple-negative breast cancer, it's overexpressed in about 80% to 90%

1113
01:08:06.868 --> 01:08:09.188
of the cases. As you can see here,

1114
01:08:10.088 --> 01:08:13.558
it has also been shown to play a functional role in breast cancer development and

1115
01:08:13.608 --> 01:08:17.456
metastasis.So fortunately, several

1116
01:08:17.496 --> 01:08:21.217
EZH2 inhibitors have been developed, as well as agents that target

1117
01:08:21.276 --> 01:08:23.967
EED, another obligate component of this

1118
01:08:25.056 --> 01:08:25.596
complex.

1119
01:08:26.547 --> 01:08:30.076
And so we wanted to determine whether EZH2 inhibitors might

1120
01:08:30.217 --> 01:08:33.896
sensitize TNBCs to AKT inhibitors by promoting some

1121
01:08:33.976 --> 01:08:36.616
kind of shift in their differentiation state.

1122
01:08:39.236 --> 01:08:43.016
To investigate this, we pre-treated a panel of TNBC cell lines with the

1123
01:08:43.056 --> 01:08:47.036
EZH2 inhibitor for several days to allow for turnover of

1124
01:08:47.116 --> 01:08:50.656
H3K27 methylation, and then added on the AKT inhibitor,

1125
01:08:51.217 --> 01:08:54.797
and found that when these agents are combined, they exert a potent cytotoxic

1126
01:08:54.856 --> 01:08:58.177
response at about 60% of the models that we evaluated,

1127
01:08:58.876 --> 01:09:01.016
as depicted by these red bars here.

1128
01:09:01.266 --> 01:09:05.116
And this, importantly, was not observed in response to either agent

1129
01:09:05.177 --> 01:09:05.616
alone.

1130
01:09:07.396 --> 01:09:10.757
These agents trigger cell death, but again, only when combined.

1131
01:09:11.257 --> 01:09:14.856
As you can see from this Incucyte, a live cell imaging analysis of

1132
01:09:14.896 --> 01:09:15.686
apoptosis,

1133
01:09:16.516 --> 01:09:19.916
they kill in a dose-dependent fashion, and they're highly synergistic.

1134
01:09:21.936 --> 01:09:25.797
Moreover, they cooperate to cause potent tumor regression in

1135
01:09:25.837 --> 01:09:29.217
vivo in very aggressive xenografts and genetically engineered

1136
01:09:29.257 --> 01:09:33.096
mouse models, as well as several PDX

1137
01:09:33.137 --> 01:09:36.816
tumors. And this type of response is highly unusual in

1138
01:09:36.837 --> 01:09:38.076
triple-negative breast cancer.

1139
01:09:39.337 --> 01:09:41.116
But what is the mechanism of action?

1140
01:09:42.217 --> 01:09:45.976
So to investigate this, we performed RNA-seq and immediately noticed that

1141
01:09:46.036 --> 01:09:49.876
EZH2 and AKT inhibitors together increase the expression of

1142
01:09:49.996 --> 01:09:53.316
normal mature luminal markers in these cells

1143
01:09:54.496 --> 01:09:57.776
and concomitantly suppress mammary stem cell markers.

1144
01:09:58.386 --> 01:10:02.256
And what was surprising to us was that this shift in cell state was

1145
01:10:02.376 --> 01:10:06.116
truly cooperative, which can be best visualized by these heat maps.

1146
01:10:06.196 --> 01:10:09.716
You can see that you need both EZH2 and AKT inhibitors to induce

1147
01:10:10.756 --> 01:10:14.526
the mature luminal signature, and you need both agents

1148
01:10:14.596 --> 01:10:17.916
to most potently suppress the basal and stem cell

1149
01:10:17.996 --> 01:10:18.656
signatures.

1150
01:10:20.996 --> 01:10:24.735
You can also really visualize this quite rapidly in patient-derived

1151
01:10:24.795 --> 01:10:27.346
tumors in vivo using cyclic immunofluorescence.

1152
01:10:28.076 --> 01:10:31.456
As you can see, tumors start out broadly expressing basal markers.

1153
01:10:31.496 --> 01:10:35.256
So for example, cytokeratin 14 is shown here in green.

1154
01:10:36.416 --> 01:10:40.296
But after just one day of treatment with the combination, tumors completely

1155
01:10:40.336 --> 01:10:44.166
adopt this more luminal-like state, as depicted by the complete shift from

1156
01:10:44.196 --> 01:10:47.856
green to purple, which marks the luminal

1157
01:10:47.865 --> 01:10:51.656
protein cytokeratin 8, with the exception of this outer

1158
01:10:51.676 --> 01:10:54.156
rim, which I'll be getting back to in a second.

1159
01:10:54.456 --> 01:10:57.876
At the same time, and these are the same tumors, you see a potent induction of

1160
01:10:57.916 --> 01:11:01.776
apoptosis in luminal cells, as depicted by the

1161
01:11:01.836 --> 01:11:03.356
yellow, which marks cleaved PARP.

1162
01:11:03.896 --> 01:11:05.826
After a few days, you start seeing clearing

1163
01:11:06.816 --> 01:11:10.756
of these cells, and after about a month, it looks like these hollowed-out

1164
01:11:10.796 --> 01:11:14.656
tumors have collapsed onto themselves like a paper bag, and there are only an

1165
01:11:14.696 --> 01:11:18.276
occasional remnant tumor knobs, which are

1166
01:11:18.316 --> 01:11:19.436
largely quiescent.

1167
01:11:20.856 --> 01:11:24.676
So if we overlay this onto a very simplified cartoon of mammary

1168
01:11:24.736 --> 01:11:28.196
gland development, we find that EZH2 and AKT inhibitors

1169
01:11:28.316 --> 01:11:32.176
cooperatively drive TNBCs to a more mature, luminal-like state.

1170
01:11:32.656 --> 01:11:36.576
And so we wondered whether this shift in differentiation state was actually

1171
01:11:36.616 --> 01:11:38.596
required for the therapeutic response.

1172
01:11:40.176 --> 01:11:43.896
We therefore looked at GATA3, which is the master developmental transcription

1173
01:11:44.016 --> 01:11:47.616
factor that drives luminal differentiation in the normal mammary

1174
01:11:47.696 --> 01:11:48.076
gland,

1175
01:11:48.876 --> 01:11:52.176
and interestingly found that both EZH2 and AKT inhibitors

1176
01:11:52.236 --> 01:11:55.856
cooperatively induce GATA3 mRNA and protein

1177
01:11:55.916 --> 01:11:56.336
levels.

1178
01:11:58.076 --> 01:12:00.025
But more importantly, when we knock it out,

1179
01:12:01.136 --> 01:12:02.836
we inhibit the therapeutic response.

1180
01:12:02.896 --> 01:12:06.436
Cells no longer die in vitro, and you can see tumors no longer

1181
01:12:06.556 --> 01:12:07.636
shrink in vivo.

1182
01:12:09.496 --> 01:12:10.776
But two questions remain.

1183
01:12:11.836 --> 01:12:15.776
First, how can we predict responses or can we predict responses?

1184
01:12:15.796 --> 01:12:18.396
And second, how does tumor cells actually die?

1185
01:12:20.136 --> 01:12:23.896
Now, because EZH2 and PI3 kinase pathway alterations occur in the

1186
01:12:23.916 --> 01:12:27.256
majority of TNBCs, we don't think they're very useful biomarkers.

1187
01:12:27.876 --> 01:12:31.496
However, principal component analysis of attack seq data can

1188
01:12:31.556 --> 01:12:35.476
readily distinguish sensitive cells in blue and resistant

1189
01:12:35.696 --> 01:12:39.416
cells in red. And so there is something inherently different

1190
01:12:39.496 --> 01:12:42.355
about the state of these cells even before treatment.

1191
01:12:43.076 --> 01:12:46.916
Moreover, we found that GATA3 could not be induced, so we

1192
01:12:47.176 --> 01:12:50.836
couldn't trigger the cell state change by EZH2 and AKT

1193
01:12:50.956 --> 01:12:52.976
inhibitors in these resistant lines.

1194
01:12:55.496 --> 01:12:59.366
We then performed an unbiased gene expression analysis in untreated

1195
01:12:59.436 --> 01:13:03.406
cells and found that the most differentially enriched signatures in

1196
01:13:03.436 --> 01:13:05.036
the resistant tumors were

1197
01:13:06.856 --> 01:13:10.186
mesenchymal signatures, whereas in the sensitive tumors, they were more

1198
01:13:10.576 --> 01:13:12.596
enriched for these basal-like genes.

1199
01:13:13.876 --> 01:13:16.976
So in other words, we believe or we hypothesize that

1200
01:13:17.736 --> 01:13:21.536
resistant cells cannot differentiate and therefore cannot die because

1201
01:13:21.556 --> 01:13:24.096
they're too undifferentiated or too mesenchymal.

1202
01:13:24.856 --> 01:13:27.376
Unfortunately, however, published mesenchymal and basal

1203
01:13:27.436 --> 01:13:31.256
signatures were not sufficient

1204
01:13:31.316 --> 01:13:34.116
to completely predict sensitivity or resistance.

1205
01:13:34.136 --> 01:13:38.016
And so we collaborated with Simon Knott and used a machine and learning approach

1206
01:13:38.056 --> 01:13:40.416
to identify a predictive signature.

1207
01:13:41.616 --> 01:13:45.416
This signature needs to be evaluated prospectively in the clinic, but we do hope

1208
01:13:45.456 --> 01:13:49.396
that it ultimately could be used in the way that the HRD signature

1209
01:13:49.456 --> 01:13:53.256
is currently being used to select patients for PARP inhibitor trials.

1210
01:13:55.216 --> 01:13:56.716
But how do they actually die?

1211
01:13:58.616 --> 01:14:02.476
To investigate this, again, we looked at our RNA-seq data and saw that apoptosis

1212
01:14:02.516 --> 01:14:06.346
signatures were upregulated. In fact, we found that this

1213
01:14:06.716 --> 01:14:10.576
one gene, BMF, was the most highly upregulated gene within this signature.

1214
01:14:10.956 --> 01:14:11.836
And as you can see,

1215
01:14:12.656 --> 01:14:15.956
both EZH2 and AKT inhibitors cooperatively induce its

1216
01:14:15.976 --> 01:14:19.792
expression.More

1217
01:14:19.812 --> 01:14:23.612
importantly, when you knock out BMF in vitro and again in vivo, you

1218
01:14:23.652 --> 01:14:27.452
inhibit cell death of the therapeutic response in vitro, and you

1219
01:14:27.512 --> 01:14:29.192
inhibit tumor regression in vivo.

1220
01:14:29.632 --> 01:14:32.752
So it is essential for this complete therapeutic response.

1221
01:14:34.372 --> 01:14:38.252
Now, when we obtained this result, we considered the normal role that BMF

1222
01:14:38.272 --> 01:14:42.112
plays in the mammary gland and noted that it drives cell death during the

1223
01:14:42.152 --> 01:14:43.412
process of involution

1224
01:14:44.232 --> 01:14:47.722
at the cessation of lactation. And so we wondered if these

1225
01:14:48.132 --> 01:14:51.032
agents were triggering a similar process in tumor cells.

1226
01:14:52.892 --> 01:14:56.772
And indeed, we found that these agents induce a transcriptional response that's

1227
01:14:56.812 --> 01:15:00.532
very reminiscent of that, that occurs during the process of involution,

1228
01:15:01.012 --> 01:15:04.332
and again, required both EZH2 and AKT

1229
01:15:04.392 --> 01:15:05.052
inhibitors.

1230
01:15:07.552 --> 01:15:11.182
We then asked, are EZH2 and AKT inhibitors activating the same

1231
01:15:11.312 --> 01:15:14.702
classical upstream signals that drive involution?

1232
01:15:14.852 --> 01:15:18.212
Specifically during the process of involution, BMF is activated by a

1233
01:15:18.252 --> 01:15:22.192
JAK1-STAT3 program, and in fact, we found that this

1234
01:15:22.252 --> 01:15:22.892
is the case.

1235
01:15:24.532 --> 01:15:27.152
JAK1 and STAT3 are cooperatively activated.

1236
01:15:27.552 --> 01:15:31.172
They're required for BMF expression, and if you ablate either one of them,

1237
01:15:31.312 --> 01:15:33.452
you abolish the therapeutic response.

1238
01:15:34.892 --> 01:15:38.422
So to summarize this part of our work in breast cancer, we found that

1239
01:15:38.472 --> 01:15:41.912
EZH2 and AKT inhibitors kill triple-negative breast cancers

1240
01:15:42.332 --> 01:15:44.612
by cooperatively promoting differentiation

1241
01:15:45.552 --> 01:15:49.412
to a more luminal-like state, which involves the cooperative induction of

1242
01:15:49.452 --> 01:15:50.052
GATA3.

1243
01:15:51.382 --> 01:15:54.632
Through a mechanism I don't really have time to talk about today, but involves the

1244
01:15:54.672 --> 01:15:58.252
de-repression of the GATA3 enhancer, and then subsequent

1245
01:15:58.392 --> 01:16:02.312
binding and transcriptional activation by FOXO1, explaining

1246
01:16:02.372 --> 01:16:06.132
the cooperativity of both the chromatin events and oncogene events

1247
01:16:06.712 --> 01:16:07.592
in this process.

1248
01:16:08.592 --> 01:16:12.382
These agents then hijack involution signals, specifically JAK1,

1249
01:16:12.512 --> 01:16:14.532
STAT3, and BMF, to trigger cell death.

1250
01:16:15.212 --> 01:16:18.612
I didn't have time to go through the data, but this is mediated

1251
01:16:18.632 --> 01:16:21.132
by STING and IL-6.

1252
01:16:22.892 --> 01:16:26.592
By contrast, cells that are resistant or models that are resistant, you don't see

1253
01:16:26.632 --> 01:16:29.731
differentiation, and you don't see this induction of BMF

1254
01:16:29.791 --> 01:16:33.741
or apoptosis. So when thinking about this in

1255
01:16:33.752 --> 01:16:35.361
the context of tumor development,

1256
01:16:36.272 --> 01:16:40.012
what this means is that EZH2 and AKT actually converge

1257
01:16:40.472 --> 01:16:44.412
to reinforce these two essential signals, ensuring that

1258
01:16:45.152 --> 01:16:48.982
both differentiation and apoptotic responses are suppressed in these tumors,

1259
01:16:49.312 --> 01:16:53.141
which is why you need both agents to initiate a therapeutic response.

1260
01:16:54.432 --> 01:16:57.552
However, this turns out to be a much broader therapeutic paradigm.

1261
01:16:57.752 --> 01:17:01.552
So specifically, we found that various oncogenic inhibitors

1262
01:17:01.932 --> 01:17:04.552
cooperate with EZH2 inhibitors in other tumor types.

1263
01:17:04.972 --> 01:17:08.872
So for example, EZH2 inhibitors also kill K-RAS mutant colorectal

1264
01:17:08.912 --> 01:17:11.952
cancers when combined with RAS pathway inhibitors.

1265
01:17:12.132 --> 01:17:15.992
They kill PTEN mutant castration-resistant prostate cancer when combined with

1266
01:17:16.052 --> 01:17:19.452
either AKT or mTORC1 inhibitors, and they kill

1267
01:17:19.512 --> 01:17:23.312
HER2-positive breast cancers, in particular, the resistant tumors,

1268
01:17:23.952 --> 01:17:27.052
when combined with these HER2 kinase inhibitors.

1269
01:17:27.192 --> 01:17:30.622
So these observations are very important on their own, and we're

1270
01:17:31.132 --> 01:17:34.762
actively using them to try to develop clinical trials for some of these and other

1271
01:17:34.772 --> 01:17:38.472
refractory tumor types. However, we've also been able to

1272
01:17:38.512 --> 01:17:42.272
generate both common and tissue-specific mechanistic themes by

1273
01:17:42.352 --> 01:17:45.912
comparing and contrasting findings in these different tissues.

1274
01:17:50.212 --> 01:17:53.852
For example, I just told you that EZH2 and AKT inhibitors kill

1275
01:17:53.892 --> 01:17:57.292
TNBCs by driving differentiation and triggering an

1276
01:17:57.352 --> 01:18:01.212
involution-like response, anyway, mediated by BMF.

1277
01:18:02.332 --> 01:18:06.292
This mechanism is thematically similar to what we see in colorectal

1278
01:18:06.332 --> 01:18:09.872
cancer. Specifically, EZH2 and RAS pathway inhibitors

1279
01:18:10.112 --> 01:18:13.992
trigger the induction of TLE4 and WNT and other WNT pathway

1280
01:18:14.072 --> 01:18:18.052
suppressors, and this results in the potent suppression of WNT signaling, which

1281
01:18:18.112 --> 01:18:20.652
in the colon drives differentiation and then cell death.

1282
01:18:21.452 --> 01:18:25.432
Moreover, like breast tissue, BMF has also been proposed to play a role

1283
01:18:25.492 --> 01:18:28.352
in normal intestinal homeostasis.

1284
01:18:28.912 --> 01:18:32.492
Specifically, it's exclusively induced in differentiated cells

1285
01:18:32.852 --> 01:18:34.252
as they migrate up the crypt

1286
01:18:35.772 --> 01:18:38.152
to promote normal intestinal cell turnover.

1287
01:18:38.332 --> 01:18:41.952
So again, these agents appear to be hijacking normal developmental

1288
01:18:42.012 --> 01:18:42.702
processes.

1289
01:18:43.572 --> 01:18:47.172
Now, this is similar but not exactly what is occurring

1290
01:18:47.332 --> 01:18:51.052
in prostate and HER2-positive breast

1291
01:18:51.092 --> 01:18:51.612
cancers.

1292
01:18:53.232 --> 01:18:56.552
So in prostate cancer, these agents trigger a catastrophic

1293
01:18:56.692 --> 01:19:00.572
reprogramming of metabolism, which shuts off both glycolysis and

1294
01:19:00.612 --> 01:19:04.232
oxidative phosphorylation through effects on MYC and HIF1A.

1295
01:19:05.222 --> 01:19:08.872
And we believe that these effects on metabolism are related to the unique

1296
01:19:08.912 --> 01:19:12.852
metabolic plasticity that's required during the development and progression of

1297
01:19:12.892 --> 01:19:13.722
prostate cancer,

1298
01:19:14.632 --> 01:19:18.032
which requires metabolic rewiring to shut off citrate

1299
01:19:18.092 --> 01:19:21.622
secretion into prostatic fluid and begin to use it as

1300
01:19:21.652 --> 01:19:25.552
oxidative phosphorylation early in tumor development, followed by a second

1301
01:19:25.612 --> 01:19:29.172
switch to aerobic glycolysis as tumors become castration-resistant.

1302
01:19:29.632 --> 01:19:33.232
So metabolic plasticity is especially critical in this tissue.

1303
01:19:35.512 --> 01:19:38.612
And finally, in HER2-positive breast cancers, we see a different type of

1304
01:19:38.652 --> 01:19:41.732
reprogramming that involves YAP, which I don't have time to discuss.

1305
01:19:42.182 --> 01:19:45.592
But I would just like to highlight that in every case, there is some kind of shift

1306
01:19:45.632 --> 01:19:49.472
in cell state, which is related to the unique biology of that tissue.

1307
01:19:50.052 --> 01:19:53.632
In all cases, cell death is mediated in part by BMF,

1308
01:19:53.972 --> 01:19:57.912
which appears to be a very important repressed PRC2

1309
01:19:57.972 --> 01:19:58.392
target.

1310
01:19:59.792 --> 01:20:02.892
So I just wanted to end with some broader conceptual

1311
01:20:02.992 --> 01:20:03.932
conclusions.

1312
01:20:04.872 --> 01:20:08.852
So I've told you today that tissue specificity in cancer arises

1313
01:20:08.892 --> 01:20:12.352
from cooperative interactions between epigenetic regulators and

1314
01:20:12.392 --> 01:20:14.052
oncogenic signaling pathways,

1315
01:20:14.992 --> 01:20:18.552
and that epigenetic events, at least in part, reinforce the most

1316
01:20:18.592 --> 01:20:21.482
important tissue-specific oncogenic signals in a given

1317
01:20:21.592 --> 01:20:25.546
tissue.Because of this, therapeutic

1318
01:20:25.596 --> 01:20:29.576
responses require the combined suppression of epigenetic and oncogenic pathways.

1319
01:20:30.276 --> 01:20:33.996
And finally, we found that some drug combinations can

1320
01:20:34.176 --> 01:20:37.846
kill tumors by hijacking normal tissue-specific pathways involved in

1321
01:20:37.876 --> 01:20:38.806
homeostasis.

1322
01:20:39.796 --> 01:20:43.696
But I would like to end up by highlighting the fact that the majority of data

1323
01:20:43.736 --> 01:20:47.156
that I showed you today really challenged the notion that drug

1324
01:20:47.176 --> 01:20:51.166
combinations must be comprised of agents that exhibit single agent activity in

1325
01:20:51.196 --> 01:20:54.756
a given tissue. And if we restrict our clinical trials in this way,

1326
01:20:55.156 --> 01:20:57.816
we are likely to miss effective combinations that work

1327
01:20:58.276 --> 01:21:01.396
cooperatively driving biological changes.

1328
01:21:03.205 --> 01:21:05.616
And with that, I'd just like to thank the people that did the work.

1329
01:21:05.876 --> 01:21:09.736
Everyone in blue worked on breast cancer, everyone in green worked on prostate

1330
01:21:09.776 --> 01:21:12.046
cancer, and everyone in red worked on colon cancer.

1331
01:21:12.466 --> 01:21:16.426
And I'd like to thank my Specify Cancer Grand Challenge team, as

1332
01:21:16.456 --> 01:21:20.396
well as CRUK and the Mark Foundation for supporting this work. Thank you.

1333
01:21:28.816 --> 01:21:29.556
Thank you, Karen.

1334
01:21:30.436 --> 01:21:34.316
And last but not least, Eileen White, who is leading CanCan,

1335
01:21:34.356 --> 01:21:37.756
the Cachexia Consortium Grand Challenge that I told you about earlier.

1336
01:21:38.676 --> 01:21:42.216
Eileen is deputy director of the Rutgers Cancer Institute, and is associate

1337
01:21:42.376 --> 01:21:45.956
director of the Ludwig Princeton branch at Princeton University.

1338
01:21:46.576 --> 01:21:50.416
As I said, she's PI for the team CanCan for the CGC, addressing

1339
01:21:50.476 --> 01:21:52.836
mechanisms that are causing cancer cachexia.

1340
01:21:53.616 --> 01:21:57.256
She's well-known for her work establishing the DNA tumor virus and an

1341
01:21:57.296 --> 01:22:00.936
oncogene it encodes, induces, or rather inhibits, I should say,

1342
01:22:01.016 --> 01:22:01.856
programmed cell death,

1343
01:22:02.816 --> 01:22:05.696
and is a homologue of the human BCL2 oncogene.

1344
01:22:06.396 --> 01:22:10.316
Her honors include election to the US National Academy of Sciences and the American

1345
01:22:10.376 --> 01:22:14.176
Academy of Arts and Sciences. She's also an elected fellow of the American

1346
01:22:14.316 --> 01:22:17.996
Association for the Advancement of Science and the American Academy of

1347
01:22:18.056 --> 01:22:21.816
Microbiology, and of course, the AACR Academy. Welcome, Eileen.

1348
01:22:22.096 --> 01:22:22.436
Thank you.

1349
01:22:34.776 --> 01:22:37.456
Well, it's my pleasure to be here and represent

1350
01:22:38.336 --> 01:22:42.016
Team CanCan and my two co-leads,

1351
01:22:42.616 --> 01:22:45.916
Tobias Janowitz and Marcos Goncalves, who

1352
01:22:46.496 --> 01:22:50.416
have led cancer cachexia sessions earlier in the meeting.

1353
01:22:56.356 --> 01:23:00.296
So cancer cachexia is a common wasting syndrome.

1354
01:23:00.316 --> 01:23:02.076
You're probably all familiar with it.

1355
01:23:02.876 --> 01:23:06.676
Cancer patients will experience a loss of

1356
01:23:06.716 --> 01:23:10.456
food intake or anorexia, sickness, weakness,

1357
01:23:10.676 --> 01:23:12.566
malaise, apathy, depression,

1358
01:23:13.416 --> 01:23:13.736
and

1359
01:23:14.536 --> 01:23:18.436
ultimately, this wasting syndrome leads to the death

1360
01:23:18.516 --> 01:23:20.616
of most patients with advanced cancer.

1361
01:23:21.146 --> 01:23:23.596
And so what we wanted to understand is

1362
01:23:23.996 --> 01:23:27.836
what is this wasting syndrome, and can

1363
01:23:27.856 --> 01:23:30.956
we stop it? And if we do stop it, the

1364
01:23:30.966 --> 01:23:34.436
expectation would be an improvement in

1365
01:23:34.696 --> 01:23:38.276
therapeutic outcome, but also an improvement in the quality of

1366
01:23:38.316 --> 01:23:41.116
life for cancer patients and their families.

1367
01:23:42.196 --> 01:23:45.876
So cancer cachexia is a poster

1368
01:23:45.996 --> 01:23:49.716
child for a systemic effect of cancer.

1369
01:23:50.716 --> 01:23:54.696
There are the well-known wasting of fat

1370
01:23:54.736 --> 01:23:56.356
and atrophy of muscle.

1371
01:23:57.416 --> 01:23:57.896
These

1372
01:23:59.756 --> 01:24:03.036
phenotypes of cancer cachexia received a lot of attention.

1373
01:24:04.216 --> 01:24:07.216
But I think where CanCan wanted to focus

1374
01:24:07.976 --> 01:24:11.666
was on identification of the tumor factors that cause these

1375
01:24:11.676 --> 01:24:15.316
systemic alterations that collectively lead to this

1376
01:24:15.356 --> 01:24:16.436
wasting syndrome.

1377
01:24:17.676 --> 01:24:21.516
So some of the tumor factors are known, and

1378
01:24:21.536 --> 01:24:25.336
they include IL6, LIP, GDF15, CCL2, and

1379
01:24:25.456 --> 01:24:29.096
so on. While many are unknown, and what they do is not

1380
01:24:29.136 --> 01:24:30.176
entirely clear.

1381
01:24:31.096 --> 01:24:34.756
But cancer cachexia is associated with systemic inflammation.

1382
01:24:35.836 --> 01:24:36.656
This includes

1383
01:24:38.156 --> 01:24:40.676
chemokines and cytokines and hormones.

1384
01:24:41.116 --> 01:24:43.176
Also an abnormal immune response.

1385
01:24:43.215 --> 01:24:45.656
There's neutrophilia that's common in cachexia.

1386
01:24:46.396 --> 01:24:50.266
There's prominent changes in liver metabolism and

1387
01:24:50.356 --> 01:24:54.256
liver function, including activation of the acute phase

1388
01:24:54.316 --> 01:24:55.796
response and inflammation.

1389
01:24:56.636 --> 01:24:59.756
These are inappropriate liver functions for someone that

1390
01:24:59.816 --> 01:25:03.396
has lost their appetite and is not eating.

1391
01:25:04.456 --> 01:25:07.636
There are systemic metabolic alterations.

1392
01:25:08.776 --> 01:25:11.376
One of the things that CanCan has discovered is that

1393
01:25:12.176 --> 01:25:16.036
a prominent metabolic feature of cancer cachexia is

1394
01:25:16.116 --> 01:25:19.016
sustained and high glucose turnover flux.

1395
01:25:19.776 --> 01:25:23.256
And again, this is an abnormal response to nutrient limitation.

1396
01:25:24.196 --> 01:25:27.976
But many of the effects that we are seeing in cancer

1397
01:25:27.996 --> 01:25:31.736
cachexia are the tumor modifying the function of the brain.

1398
01:25:32.796 --> 01:25:35.696
And this, I think, is very fascinating in that

1399
01:25:36.576 --> 01:25:40.416
a lot of the wasting is caused by

1400
01:25:40.536 --> 01:25:43.476
actually the patients lose their appetite.

1401
01:25:43.596 --> 01:25:47.566
So understanding how the various mechanisms by

1402
01:25:47.596 --> 01:25:50.696
which that occurs is very important.

1403
01:25:51.256 --> 01:25:55.036
Patients with cancer cachexia get depressed.

1404
01:25:55.536 --> 01:25:59.196
They lose motivation, so there's no reward for

1405
01:25:59.236 --> 01:26:02.276
positive experiences. They have apathy.

1406
01:26:02.356 --> 01:26:05.136
They have reduced physical activity.

1407
01:26:05.216 --> 01:26:08.616
I'm sure all of the clinicians in the audience will

1408
01:26:09.576 --> 01:26:12.516
be very familiar with these phenotypes.

1409
01:26:12.546 --> 01:26:16.496
So these are the types of things that we have focused on, and

1410
01:26:16.556 --> 01:26:19.536
I'll try to give you a few examples of what we

1411
01:26:19.616 --> 01:26:23.496
found in our course with

1412
01:26:24.116 --> 01:26:27.956
Team CanCan. And I'll start with brain signaling

1413
01:26:28.016 --> 01:26:31.475
drivers of cancer cachexia. So the O'Reilly and Co.

1414
01:26:31.586 --> 01:26:32.876
Labs are leaders

1415
01:26:33.916 --> 01:26:36.976
in the field of understanding the hormone

1416
01:26:37.036 --> 01:26:40.556
GDF15, which acts in the brain through its receptor,

1417
01:26:40.676 --> 01:26:44.236
GFRA1. And what they did was identify a novel

1418
01:26:44.676 --> 01:26:48.396
neuronal circuit that results in the production of glucocorticoids,

1419
01:26:48.756 --> 01:26:52.404
and that can lead to muscle wasting.And the

1420
01:26:52.424 --> 01:26:53.404
Janowitz lab

1421
01:26:54.344 --> 01:26:57.324
made some important discoveries, including

1422
01:26:57.844 --> 01:27:01.564
that the cachectic factor IL-6 that's produced by the

1423
01:27:01.644 --> 01:27:04.884
tumor acts in the brain to induce a novel

1424
01:27:05.324 --> 01:27:09.004
neuronal circuit that limits the production

1425
01:27:09.164 --> 01:27:13.144
of dopamine, and that limitation in dopamine

1426
01:27:13.184 --> 01:27:16.844
leads to apathy, another common phenotype

1427
01:27:17.484 --> 01:27:19.124
of cancer cachexia.

1428
01:27:22.204 --> 01:27:26.064
The next question we wanted to ask is: Is there a

1429
01:27:26.584 --> 01:27:29.844
dietary remedy for this wasting syndrome?

1430
01:27:30.364 --> 01:27:34.044
And this is an important question because normally if you take a cachectic

1431
01:27:34.104 --> 01:27:37.604
patient and try to maintain their calorie intake,

1432
01:27:38.044 --> 01:27:39.324
it doesn't really help.

1433
01:27:40.384 --> 01:27:44.144
So one of the things that we found, and I'll tell you about it in a

1434
01:27:44.204 --> 01:27:45.884
moment, is if you put

1435
01:27:47.184 --> 01:27:50.644
mice on a high-fat

1436
01:27:50.744 --> 01:27:54.084
diet, so a high-calorie

1437
01:27:54.804 --> 01:27:58.084
diet, it actually worsens cancer cachexia.

1438
01:27:58.104 --> 01:28:01.804
And the Papagiannopoulos lab worked out the mechanism

1439
01:28:02.264 --> 01:28:05.424
is that in the context of a high-fat diet, this causes

1440
01:28:05.764 --> 01:28:09.464
production of prostaglandin E2 in the

1441
01:28:09.504 --> 01:28:13.044
tumor, and that signals through the vagus

1442
01:28:13.144 --> 01:28:14.804
nerve to induce

1443
01:28:16.124 --> 01:28:19.364
exacerbated cancer cachexia in mice.

1444
01:28:19.724 --> 01:28:20.224
And they also

1445
01:28:21.504 --> 01:28:24.884
discovered various interventions to interfere with

1446
01:28:24.924 --> 01:28:27.824
this function of prostaglandin E2

1447
01:28:28.464 --> 01:28:32.084
produced by high-fat diet and

1448
01:28:32.544 --> 01:28:33.424
from the tumor.

1449
01:28:34.324 --> 01:28:38.304
The next we wanted to address the metabolic drivers of cancer

1450
01:28:38.384 --> 01:28:39.064
cachexia.

1451
01:28:39.984 --> 01:28:43.764
We have developed various genetically engineered mouse models of

1452
01:28:43.824 --> 01:28:47.484
cachexia. Here is an example from what we

1453
01:28:47.544 --> 01:28:51.184
found in mouse models of pancreas cancer.

1454
01:28:51.904 --> 01:28:51.964
The

1455
01:28:52.784 --> 01:28:56.024
mice lose weight. They lose lean mass and fat mass.

1456
01:28:56.404 --> 01:28:59.204
There's a genetic model and an orthotopic model.

1457
01:28:59.264 --> 01:29:02.944
The results are the same. And if we characterize

1458
01:29:04.204 --> 01:29:07.084
the global metabolism of these animals, you see that

1459
01:29:08.144 --> 01:29:11.984
in the orange, that the mice with pancreas cancer

1460
01:29:13.024 --> 01:29:16.874
lose their appetite and reduce their food intake, and they reduce their

1461
01:29:16.944 --> 01:29:20.044
locomotion, and this is true in both of the mouse

1462
01:29:20.124 --> 01:29:24.104
models of pancreas cancer. We then are in the

1463
01:29:24.164 --> 01:29:28.024
midst of performing a systemic metabolic analysis

1464
01:29:28.084 --> 01:29:31.924
of what metabolically is going wrong in these animals with

1465
01:29:32.264 --> 01:29:36.244
pancreas cancer. And one thing stood out very early

1466
01:29:36.344 --> 01:29:40.284
on in our metabolic analysis, in that

1467
01:29:40.344 --> 01:29:43.724
the mice with pancreas cancer had low serotonin

1468
01:29:44.284 --> 01:29:47.024
and high kynurenine. Okay, these are

1469
01:29:47.984 --> 01:29:51.124
shown here, and we've seen this in multiple models

1470
01:29:51.604 --> 01:29:55.524
of mouse models of cancer. Here's an example of the

1471
01:29:55.584 --> 01:29:59.384
same information from lung cancer, and it's also been

1472
01:29:59.424 --> 01:30:01.324
reported in patients with cancer.

1473
01:30:02.164 --> 01:30:06.044
So what does this mean? Well, this suggests that metabolically what's

1474
01:30:06.104 --> 01:30:09.984
happening in these mouse models of pancreas cancer

1475
01:30:10.044 --> 01:30:13.744
cachexia is a disruption in normal tryptophan

1476
01:30:13.804 --> 01:30:17.524
metabolism. So tryptophan can be

1477
01:30:18.084 --> 01:30:20.684
metabolized to generate serotonin.

1478
01:30:21.324 --> 01:30:25.024
It can be metabolized by the kynurenine

1479
01:30:25.104 --> 01:30:28.304
pathway to produce kynurenine and eventually NAD,

1480
01:30:28.984 --> 01:30:32.904
or it can be metabolized by the microbiome to produce

1481
01:30:32.964 --> 01:30:36.664
indoles. And our data was suggesting that from

1482
01:30:37.104 --> 01:30:40.664
the changes we were seeing in the tryptophan pathway was that

1483
01:30:40.724 --> 01:30:42.944
cachexia was driving

1484
01:30:43.824 --> 01:30:47.804
the pathway down the kynurenine

1485
01:30:47.904 --> 01:30:50.504
pathway and away from the serotonin pathway.

1486
01:30:50.904 --> 01:30:53.744
Why would that be important in cachexia?

1487
01:30:53.804 --> 01:30:57.464
Well, it could be very important because serotonin has an

1488
01:30:57.504 --> 01:30:58.744
important role in

1489
01:30:59.884 --> 01:31:03.124
preventing depression. And high

1490
01:31:03.144 --> 01:31:07.104
kynurenine has a role in muscle wasting and immune

1491
01:31:07.164 --> 01:31:10.923
suppression. So we thought that this metabolic

1492
01:31:10.983 --> 01:31:14.904
alteration in the tryptophan pathway might explain some

1493
01:31:14.944 --> 01:31:17.564
of the phenotypes we see in cancer cachexia.

1494
01:31:18.244 --> 01:31:21.564
And there are possible ways to intervene in this pathway.

1495
01:31:21.984 --> 01:31:25.304
We can provide a selective serotonin reuptake

1496
01:31:25.344 --> 01:31:29.264
inhibitor and increase serotonin levels and see if that

1497
01:31:29.304 --> 01:31:31.544
ameliorates a depression-like phenotype.

1498
01:31:31.894 --> 01:31:35.804
We can do the same by providing the metabolic substrate of

1499
01:31:35.864 --> 01:31:39.804
serotonin 5-HTP, or we can block kynurenine

1500
01:31:39.864 --> 01:31:42.204
production by using an IDO inhibitor.

1501
01:31:42.744 --> 01:31:44.144
And all of these

1502
01:31:45.504 --> 01:31:49.424
interventions produce the same phenotype, and I'll just show you the

1503
01:31:49.464 --> 01:31:50.424
results with the

1504
01:31:51.244 --> 01:31:52.084
SSRI.

1505
01:31:54.064 --> 01:31:56.464
And here you have an example of mice with PDAC,

1506
01:31:57.664 --> 01:32:00.584
with and without a serotonin reuptake inhibitor.

1507
01:32:00.624 --> 01:32:03.884
Here is food intake. The serotonin reuptake inhibitor

1508
01:32:04.304 --> 01:32:07.704
improves it, as well as it improves

1509
01:32:08.804 --> 01:32:10.224
pedestrian locomotion.

1510
01:32:12.224 --> 01:32:16.104
And this led us to the question, well, if the mice have an abnormal

1511
01:32:16.124 --> 01:32:20.024
tryptophan metabolism and they lack serotonin and they're depressed,

1512
01:32:20.444 --> 01:32:22.524
how do you tell if a mouse is depressed?

1513
01:32:23.024 --> 01:32:24.964
Okay, that's an important question for us.

1514
01:32:25.424 --> 01:32:29.224
And it turns out you can, because mice are good

1515
01:32:29.404 --> 01:32:30.084
swimmers,

1516
01:32:31.364 --> 01:32:35.284
and if the mouse is depressed, the mice

1517
01:32:35.304 --> 01:32:38.904
will just give up swimming. And so what we have here are

1518
01:32:38.944 --> 01:32:39.784
normal mice.

1519
01:32:43.184 --> 01:32:43.864
No tumor.

1520
01:32:45.954 --> 01:32:48.604
No tumor. And this is a PDAC mouse

1521
01:32:49.524 --> 01:32:53.492
with a tumor.And this is a pDEC mouse

1522
01:32:53.992 --> 01:32:57.472
with a tumor and an SSRI,

1523
01:32:58.132 --> 01:33:01.852
and you can see what happens is that what we've

1524
01:33:01.872 --> 01:33:05.532
done is that by correcting the defect in tryptophan

1525
01:33:05.552 --> 01:33:09.132
metabolism, we've cured the depression in the mice, and they keep

1526
01:33:09.232 --> 01:33:10.992
on swimming.

1527
01:33:12.232 --> 01:33:14.652
But then what happens to the wasting phenotype?

1528
01:33:15.452 --> 01:33:16.952
And you can see here that

1529
01:33:17.772 --> 01:33:21.732
with or without a serotonin reuptake inhibitor, there's no improvement

1530
01:33:21.772 --> 01:33:25.372
in body weight, fat mass, lean mass, or survival of the

1531
01:33:25.492 --> 01:33:29.172
animals. And so what that tells us is that the

1532
01:33:29.832 --> 01:33:32.912
disruption in the production of tryptophan

1533
01:33:33.752 --> 01:33:36.722
in pancreas cancer cachexia is

1534
01:33:36.812 --> 01:33:40.542
specifically affecting depression and

1535
01:33:40.592 --> 01:33:43.672
is completely independent from the wasting

1536
01:33:46.112 --> 01:33:48.252
phenotype. And so this is what we think.

1537
01:33:48.292 --> 01:33:50.812
In cancer, you have loss of

1538
01:33:51.612 --> 01:33:55.332
serotonin because tryptophan is being diverted down the kynurenine

1539
01:33:55.412 --> 01:33:55.932
pathway

1540
01:33:56.891 --> 01:33:58.652
by activation of IDO.

1541
01:34:00.572 --> 01:34:04.182
Okay. Oh, and one more important thing is that,

1542
01:34:04.972 --> 01:34:06.892
many cancer patients are depressed.

1543
01:34:07.852 --> 01:34:11.252
This suggests that there might be a biochemical basis for that

1544
01:34:11.272 --> 01:34:14.212
